{"title_page": "George Bassett", "text_new": "{{otherpeople}}\n[[File:George Bassett's memorial in Sheffield General Cemetery (portrait).jpg|thumb|George Bassett's memorial in Sheffield General Cemetery]]\n'''George Bassett''' (1818&ndash;1886) was the founder in 1842 of [[Bassett's]], a [[confectionery]] firm in [[Sheffield]].<ref name=Cadbury>[http://www.cadbury.com/ourbrands/otherfavouritebrands/candy/pages/bassetts2.aspx www.cadbury.com] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100729230930/http://www.cadbury.com/ourbrands/otherfavouritebrands/candy/Pages/Bassetts2.aspx |date=2010-07-29 }} Our brands - Bassett's</ref> The company (after his death) introduced [[Liquorice allsorts]]. He went on to become [[Lord Mayor of Sheffield|Mayor of Sheffield]] (1876).<ref name=Indexers>[http://www.sheffieldindexers.com/MasterCutlersMayors.html The Sheffield Indexers: Master Cutlers and Mayors]</ref> Whilst Mayor, he had US President [[Ulysses S. Grant]] as a house guest.<ref name=Bassett>[http://www.bassettbranches.org/newsletters/2005/20051120/20051120.shtml Bassett Family Association] Newsletter 2005</ref> He was born in [[Ashover]], [[Derbyshire]], and married as his first wife, Sarah Hodgson, they had six daughters. He married as his second wife, Sarah Ann Hague: they had two sons.<ref name=Bassett/> He is buried in [[Sheffield General Cemetery]] with his second wife, Sarah Ann.<ref name=Bassett/>.\n\nBassett was the great-uncle of noted conservationist and countryside campaigner [[Ethel Haythornthwaite]] (1894\u20131986).<ref name=\"Sheffield HOD\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/news/latest/sheffield-s-heritage-open-days-2018-why-city-s-force-of-nature-ethel-haythornthwaite-is-responsible-for-country-s-green-belt-1-9327702|title=Sheffield\u2019s Heritage Open Days 2018: Why city\u2019s \u2018force of nature\u2019 Ethel Haythornthwaite is responsible for country\u2019s Green Belt|author=Richard Blackledge|work=The Star|accessdate=8 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bassett, George}}\n[[Category:1818 births]]\n[[Category:1886 deaths]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in confectionery]]\n[[Category:Lord Mayors of Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Burials at Sheffield General Cemetery]]\n[[Category:English company founders]]\n[[Category:People from Ashover]]\n\n{{UK-business-bio-stub}}\n{{England-mayor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{otherpeople}}\n[[File:George Bassett's memorial in Sheffield General Cemetery (portrait).jpg|thumb|George Bassett's memorial in Sheffield General Cemetery]]\n'''George Bassett''' (1818&ndash;1886) was the founder in 1842 of [[Bassett's]], a [[confectionery]] firm in [[Sheffield]].<ref name=Cadbury>[http://www.cadbury.com/ourbrands/otherfavouritebrands/candy/pages/bassetts2.aspx www.cadbury.com] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100729230930/http://www.cadbury.com/ourbrands/otherfavouritebrands/candy/Pages/Bassetts2.aspx |date=2010-07-29 }} Our brands - Bassett's</ref> The company (after his death) introduced [[Liquorice allsorts]]. He went on to become [[Lord Mayor of Sheffield|Mayor of Sheffield]] (1876).<ref name=Indexers>[http://www.sheffieldindexers.com/MasterCutlersMayors.html The Sheffield Indexers: Master Cutlers and Mayors]</ref> Whilst Mayor, he had US President [[Ulysses S. Grant]] as a house guest.<ref name=Bassett>[http://www.bassettbranches.org/newsletters/2005/20051120/20051120.shtml Bassett Family Association] Newsletter 2005</ref> He was born in [[Ashover]], [[Derbyshire]], and married as his first wife, Sarah Hodgson, they had six daughters. He married as his second wife, Sarah Ann Hague: they had two sons.<ref name=Bassett/> He is buried in [[Sheffield General Cemetery]].<ref name=Bassett/>.\n\nBassett was the great-uncle of noted conservationist and countryside campaigner [[Ethel Haythornthwaite]] (1894\u20131986).<ref name=\"Sheffield HOD\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/news/latest/sheffield-s-heritage-open-days-2018-why-city-s-force-of-nature-ethel-haythornthwaite-is-responsible-for-country-s-green-belt-1-9327702|title=Sheffield\u2019s Heritage Open Days 2018: Why city\u2019s \u2018force of nature\u2019 Ethel Haythornthwaite is responsible for country\u2019s Green Belt|author=Richard Blackledge|work=The Star|accessdate=8 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bassett, George}}\n[[Category:1818 births]]\n[[Category:1886 deaths]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in confectionery]]\n[[Category:Lord Mayors of Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Burials at Sheffield General Cemetery]]\n[[Category:English company founders]]\n[[Category:People from Ashover]]\n\n{{UK-business-bio-stub}}\n{{England-mayor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Maerk", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sarah also buried in same grave", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Bassett"}
{"title_page": "FK Metalurg Skopje", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club |\n  clubname = Metalurg Skopje |\n  image    = FK Metalurg Skopje.png |\n  fullname = Fudbalski klub Metalurg Skopje|\n  founded  = {{Start date and age|1964}} |\n  nickname = \u041c\u0435\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0443\u0440\u0446\u0438 (Metallurgists) |\n  ground   = [[\u017delezarnica Stadium]]|\n  capacity = 3,000|\n  chairman = |\n  manager  = |\n  league   = |\n  season = [[2016\u201317 Macedonian Second Football League|2016\u201317]] |\n  position = [[Macedonian Second Football League|Macedonian Second League]], 9th (relegated) |\npattern_la1=|pattern_b1=_whitethinlines|pattern_so1=_blacktop|\n leftarm1=008000|body1=008000|rightarm1=008000|shorts1=008000|socks1=008000|\n  pattern_la2=_shouldersonwhite|pattern_b2=_shouldersonwhite|pattern_ra2=_shouldersonwhite|\n  leftarm2=FFFFFF|body2=FFFFFF|rightarm2=FFFFFF|shorts2=FFFFFF|socks2=FFFFFF|\n| website = https://web.archive.org/web/20110717083732/http://www.fcmetalurg.com.mk/\n}}\n\n'''FK Metalurg''' ({{lang-mk|\u0424\u041a \u041c\u0435\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0443\u0440\u0433}}) is a football club from [[Skopje]], [[North Macedonia]]. They were recently competed in the [[Macedonian Second Football League|Macedonian Second League]].\n\n==History==\nThe club was founded in 1964.\n\nMetalurg has entered the [[Macedonian First Football League|Macedonian First League]] in the 1992\u201393 season and were relegated the same year. After playing 15 seasons in the [[Macedonian Second Football League|Macedonian Second League]] they were back in the Macedonian First League for the 2008\u201309 season. In the 2009\u201310 season they finished in 3rd place and played in Europe for the first time in club history.<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2011/matches/round=2000124/match=2002580/postmatch/commentary/index.html Qaraba\u011f&nbsp;\u2013 Metalurg Skopje] UEFA.com {{in lang|en}}</ref> In 2015\u201316 season Metalurg was relegated from the First League after 8 seasons.\n\n==Season-by-season record==\nA '''season-by-season record''' of Metalurg league performances:\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:right\"\n|-\n!Season&nbsp;&nbsp;\n!P\n!W\n!D\n!L\n!F\n!A\n!Pts\n!Pos\n!Notes\n|-\n|1992\u201393|1992\u201393||34||12||7||15||37||42||31||15||align=left| [[Macedonian First League]] (relegated)\n|-\n|2008\u201309|2008\u201309||30||6||11||13||25||35||29||9||align=left| Macedonian First League\n|-\n|2009\u201310|2009\u201310||26||12||11||3||35||16||47||3||align=left| Macedonian First League\n|-\n|2010\u201311|2010\u201311||33||17||10||6||48||24||61||2||align=left| Macedonian First League\n|-\n|2011\u201312|2011\u201312||33||19||10||4||53||16||67||2||align=left| Macedonian First League\n|-\n|2012\u201313|2012\u201313||33||18||9||6||48||28||63||2||align=left| Macedonian First League\n|-\n|2013\u201314|2013\u201314||33||16||11||6||48||29||59||3||align=left| Macedonian First League\n|-\n|2014\u201315|2014\u201315||32||8||9||15||34||42||33||6||align=left| Macedonian First League\n|-\n|2015\u201316|2015\u201316||33||5||4||22||27||65||19||9||align=left| Macedonian First League (relegated)\n|-\n|2016\u201317|2016\u201317||27||7||5||15||29||48||26||9||align=left| Macedonian Second League (relegated)\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n'''{{Flagicon|SR Macedonia}} [[Macedonian Republic Football League|Macedonian Republic League]]:'''\n*'''Winners (1):''' 1987\n\n'''{{Flagicon|Macedonia}} [[Macedonian First Football League|Macedonian First League]]:'''\n*Runners-up (3): [[2010\u201311 Macedonian First Football League|2010\u201311]], [[2011\u201312 Macedonian First Football League|2011\u201312]], [[2012\u201313 Macedonian First Football League|2012\u201313]]\n\n'''{{Flagicon|Macedonia}} [[Macedonian Second Football League|Macedonian Second League]]:'''\n*Runners-up (2): [[1993\u201394 Macedonian Second Football League|1993\u201394]], [[2007\u201308 Macedonian Second Football League|2007\u201308]]\n\n'''{{Flagicon|Macedonia}} [[Macedonian Football Cup]]:'''\n*'''Winners (1):''' [[2010\u201311 Macedonian Football Cup|2010\u201311]]\n*Runners-up (1): [[2013\u201314 Macedonian Football Cup|2013\u201314]]\n\n'''{{Flagicon|Macedonia}} [[Macedonian Football Supercup]]:'''\n*Runners-up (1): [[Macedonian Football Supercup#2011|2011]]\n\n==Metalurg in Europe==\n* Q = qualifier\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Season\n! Competition\n! Round\n! Club\n! Home\n! Away\n! Agg.\n!\n|-\n| [[2010\u201311 UEFA Europa League|2010\u201311]]\n| [[UEFA Europa League]]\n| [[2010\u201311 UEFA Europa League#First qualifying round|Q1]]\n| {{flagicon|Azerbaijan}} [[Qaraba\u011f FK]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\u20131\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\u20134\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''2\u20135'''\n| [[File:Symbol delete vote.svg|17px]]\n|-\n| [[2011\u201312 UEFA Europa League|2011\u201312]]\n| [[UEFA Europa League]]\n| [[2011\u201312 UEFA Europa League#Second qualifying round|Q2]]\n| {{flagicon|Bulgaria}} [[PFC Lokomotiv Sofia]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 0\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\u20133\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''2\u20133'''\n| [[File:Symbol delete vote.svg|17px]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[2012\u201313 UEFA Europa League|2012\u201313]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[UEFA Europa League]]\n| [[2012\u201313 UEFA Europa League#First qualifying round|Q1]]\n| {{flagicon|Malta}} [[Birkirkara F.C.|Birkirkara FC]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 0\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\u20132\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''2\u20132''' ([[Away goals rule|a]])\n| [[File:Symbol keep vote.svg|17px]]\n|-\n| [[2012\u201313 UEFA Europa League#Second qualifying round|Q2]]\n| {{flagicon|Poland}} [[Ruch Chorz\u00f3w]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 0\u20133\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\u20133\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''1\u20136'''\n| [[File:Symbol delete vote.svg|17px]]\n|-\n| [[2013\u201314 UEFA Europa League|2013\u201314]]\n| [[UEFA Europa League]]\n| [[2013\u201314 UEFA Europa League#