rtainment.\n\n==Sequels==\n{{main article|Alvin and the Chipmunks in film#Live-action/animated films}}\nA sequel, titled ''[[Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel]]'', was released on December 23, 2009. [[Zachary Levi]] joined the cast to replace [[Jason Lee (actor)|Jason Lee]] due to his small role and because of his role on ''[[My Name Is Earl]]''; the main cast members reprised their roles for the sequel and the film also re-introduced [[the Chipettes]]. A third film, titled ''[[Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked]]'', was released on December 16, 2011. A fourth film, titled ''[[Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Road Chip]]'', was released on December 18, 2015.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0952640|Alvin and the Chipmunks}}\n* {{tcmdb title|664892|Alvin and the Chipmunks}}\n* {{bcdb title|94777|Alvin and the Chipmunks}}\n* {{Allmovie title|387020|Alvin and the Chipmunks}}\n* {{mojo title|alvinandthechipmunks|Alvin and the Chipmunks}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|1184827-alvin_and_the_chipmunks|Alvin and the Chipmunks}}\n* {{metacritic film|alvin-and-the-chipmunks|Alvin and the Chipmunks}}\n\n{{Alvin and the Chipmunks}}\n{{Tim Hill}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alvin And The Chipmunks}}\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:2007 soundtracks]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2000s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:American Christmas films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Alvin and the Chipmunks albums]]\n[[Category:Alvin and the Chipmunks films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Live-action films based on animated series]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:Regency Enterprises films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Tim Hill]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Christopher Lennertz]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Alvin and the Chipmunks\n| image_size     = \n| image          = Alvin and the Chipmunks2007.jpg\n| alt            = <!-- See WP:ALT -->\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Tim Hill (director)|Tim Hill]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Janice Karman]]\n* [[Ross Bagdasarian Jr.]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Jon Vitti]]\n* [[Will McRobb and Chris Viscardi|Will McRobb]]\n* [[Will McRobb and Chris Viscardi|Chris Viscardi]]\n}}\n| story          = Jon Vitti\n| based on       = {{Based on|[[Alvin and the Chipmunks]]||[[Ross Bagdasarian Sr.]]}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Jason Lee (actor)|Jason Lee]]\n* [[David Cross]]\n* [[Cameron Richardson]]\n* [[Jane Lynch]]\n* [[Justin Long]]\n* [[Matthew Gray Gubler]]\n* [[Jesse McCartney]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Christopher Lennertz]]\n| cinematography = [[Peter Lyons Collister]]\n| editing        = [[Peter E. Berger|Peter Berger]]\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Fox 2000 Pictures]]<ref name=afi>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/64130?sid=bd667657-76d8-459e-be66-564e5815d612&sr=3.7860656&cp=1&pos=1|title= Alvin and the Chipmunks (2007) |work=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]] |accessdate=June 20, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Regency Enterprises]]<ref name=afi/>\n}}\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]<ref name=afi/>\n| released       = {{Film date|2007|12|14}}\n| runtime        = 92 minutes<ref name=afi/>\n| country        = United States<ref name=afi/>\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $60 million<ref name=mojo>{{citeweb|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=alvinandthechipmunks.htm|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref>\n| gross          = $361.3 million<ref name=mojo/>\n}}\n'''''Alvin and the Chipmunks''''' is a 2007 American [[live action]] [[computer animation|computer animated]] [[musical film|musical]] [[comedy film]] directed by [[Tim Hill (director)|Tim Hill]]. Based on [[Alvin and the Chipmunks|the characters of the same name]] created by [[Ross Bagdasarian Sr.]], the film stars [[Jason Lee (actor)|Jason Lee]], [[David Cross]], [[Cameron Richardson]], and [[Jane Lynch]] with the voices of [[Justin Long]], [[Matthew Gray Gubler]] and [[Jesse McCartney]]. \n\nIt was released worldwide on December 14, 2007, by [[20th Century Fox]] and produced by [[Fox 2000 Pictures]] and [[Regency Enterprises]]. ''Alvin and the Chipmunks'' grossed $217 million in [[North America]] and $361 million at the box office worldwide on a budget of $60 million<ref name=\"mtv\" /><ref name=mojo/> and was the seventh-best-selling DVD of 2008, earning over $101 million. Despite this, the film received generally unfavorable reviews from critics.\n\n''Alvin and the Chipmunks'' is the first live action/animated film [[Alvin and the Chipmunks in film|starring Alvin and the Chipmunks]] since ''[[Little Alvin and the Mini-Munks]]'' was released in 2003, as that film features puppetry used for the Chipmunks and this film features computer animation used for them. The film was followed by three sequels: ''[[Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel]]'', released on December 23, 2009; ''[[Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked]]'', released on December 16, 2011; and ''[[Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Road Chip]]'', released on December 18, 2015<ref>{{cite web|last=Kit|first=Borys|title='Alvin and the Chipmunks 4' Finds a Director (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/alvin-chipmunks-4-finds-a-758855|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=December 18, 2014|date=December 18, 2014}}</ref>, which all received unfavorable reviews from critics.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- See WP:FILMPLOT before editing. Plot summaries are usually between 400 and 700 words. -->\nA tree that three young chipmunk brothers [[Alvin and the Chipmunks|Alvin, Simon, and Theodore]] live in is cut down and driven to [[Los Angeles]] after JETT Records purchases it as a Christmas tree. There, struggling songwriter and composer [[Ross Bagdasarian, Sr.|David Seville]] has his latest demo rejected by JETT Records' calm and nice chief executive, [[Ian Hawke]], his college roommate, who suggests that Dave give up writing songs. The Chipmunks hop into a [[basket]] of [[muffins]] that Dave stole from one of Ian's coworkers, and follow Dave home. Once there, Dave discovers the Chipmunks and kicks them out, only to hear them sing \"[[Only You (And You Alone)]].\" Dave then makes a deal with the Chipmunks to sing songs he writes in exchange for shelter. Unfortunately, when Dave tries to present the Chipmunks to Ian, they fail to sing due to [[stage fright]]. The day worsens as Dave is [[Involuntary termination of employment|dismissed]] from his advertising job due to the Chipmunks having ruined his presentation. While hosting dinner with former girlfriend Claire, Dave struggles to hide the Chipmunks after Alvin attempts to create a romantic atmosphere, making Claire uncomfortable and causing her to leave. To make it up to him, the Chipmunks sing Dave's song to Ian, prompting Ian to sign a record deal.\n\nThe Chipmunks quickly become an international success. When Dave expresses concern for their well-being and insists that the Chipmunks are simply kids, Ian convinces them that Dave is holding them back. After a misunderstanding, the Chipmunks choose to live with Ian, who was revealed to be an evil thief who wants to keep the Chipmunks forever. Once there, he spoils them with candy and toys. Once they set off on a nationwide coast-to-coast tour, Ian takes advantage of their na\u00efvet\u00e9 by overworking them constantly. Frustrated by what Ian has done to the Chipmunks, Dave decides to infiltrate their concert to reunite with them. Before their tour can begin, a veterinarian explains to Ian that the Chipmunks' voices have worn due to exhaustion and suggests that they take a long rest, but as Ian doesn't want to cancel the concert and give refunds, he advises the Chipmunks to lip-sync. With Claire's help, Dave is allowed into the concert; the Chipmunks see Dave and decide to ruin the show. Ian locks the Chipmunks in a cage and prepares to take them on their world tour, escaping in his limousine with Dave in pursuit, but the Chipmunks have already escaped to Dave's car; Dave happily admits that he loves them like his own family. Meanwhile, Ian is shocked to see that the Chipmunks have replaced themselves with their merchandising dolls and is now unemployed as punishment for his crimes.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Justin Long]] as Alvin Seville (voice)\n**[[Ross Bagdasarian, Jr.]] as Alvin Seville (singing voice)\n*[[Matthew Gray Gubler]] as Simon Seville (voice)\n**[[Steve Vining]] as Simon Seville (singing voice)\n*[[Jesse McCartney]] as Theodore Seville (voice)\n**[[Janice Karman]] as Theodore Seville (singing voice)\n*[[Jason Lee (actor)|Jason Lee]] as [[David Seville|David \"Dave\" Seville]], a struggling songwriter and father figure to Alvin, Simon and Theodore \n*[[David Cross]] as Ian Hawke, the chief executive at JETT Records\n*[[Cameron Richardson]] as Claire Wilson, Dave's ex-girlfriend\n*[[Jane Lynch]] as Gail, an advertising executive and Dave's former boss\n*[[Kevin Symons]] as Ted\n*[[Frank Maharajh]] as Barry\n*Veronica Alicino as Amy\n\n== Production ==\n[[Ross Bagdasarian Jr.]], the son of [[Alvin and the Chipmunks]] creator [[Ross Bagdasarian Sr.]] who revived the franchise after his father's death, dreamed of making a live-action ''Alvin'' film since 1997, \"and the dream has had many nightmare moments.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channel24.co.za/Movies/Features/A-Chipmunk-Interview-part-1-20081201|title=A Chipmunk Interview \u2013 part 1|last=|first=|date=December 27, 2007|work=Channel 24|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103210050/https://www.channel24.co.za/Movies/Features/A-Chipmunk-Interview-part-1-20081201|archive-date=3 January 2020|accessdate=December 22, 2019}}</ref> On September 17, 2004, [[Fox 2000 Pictures]], [[20th Century Fox Animation]] and Bagdasarian Productions announced they would collaborate to create a live-action computer-generated film starring [[Alvin and the Chipmunks]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Brodesser|first=Claude|date=September 14, 2004|url=https://variety.com/2004/film/markets-festivals/alvin-to-squeak-again-1117910455/|title=\u2018Alvin\u2019 to squeak again|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref> On April 17, 2005, ''[[The Simpsons]]'' writer [[Jon Vitti]] was revealed to be writing the screenplay.<ref>{{cite web|last=Brodesser|first=Claude|date=April 17, 2005|url=https://variety.com/2005/film/news/fox-animation-ups-cohen-1117921226/|title=Fox Animation ups Cohen|work=Variety|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref> On January 24, 2007, it was announced [[Tim Hill (director)|Tim Hill]] was in talks with Fox to direct the film.<ref>{{cite web|last=LaPorte|first=Nicole|date=January 24, 2007|url=https://variety.com/2007/scene/markets-festivals/hill-to-direct-chipmunks-1117958050/|title=Hill to direct \u2018Chipmunks\u2019|work=Variety|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref> On March 7, 2007, [[Jason Lee (actor)|Jason Lee]] joined the project to play David Seville,<ref>{{cite web|last=Mcnary|first=Dave|date=March 7, 2007|url=https://variety.com/2007/digital/news/chipmunks-befriend-earl-star-1117960746/?jwsource=cl|title=\u2018Chipmunks\u2019 befriend \u2018Earl\u2019 star|work=Variety|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref> and [[Cameron Richardson]] signed on March 21.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dodd|first=Stacy|date=March 21, 2007|url=https://variety.com/2007/scene/markets-festivals/cameron-richardson-2-1117961581/|title=Cameron Richardson|work=Variety|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref> David was a more clean-cut character for Lee than his past roles, which he appreciated.<ref name = \"LAtimespro\"/>\n\nBagdasarian and his wife, [[Janice Karman]], had always voiced the chipmunks since they revived the franchise; however, for the film, they were replaced by younger, more well-known actors for marketing reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1047080/alvin-chipmunks-stay-in-the-family|title=Alvin, Chipmunks Stay In The Family|date=December 11, 2007|work=Billboard|accessdate=December 27, 2019}}</ref> For recording, the chipmunk voice actors spoke their lines slowly to be sped up to normal speed in post-production; McCartney described it as a \"tedious process,\" where \"it could take 40 takes for one line.\" He was such an Alvin and the Chipmunks fan that he even owned the album ''[[Chipmunk Punk]]'' (1980), and studied [[Alvin and the Chipmunks (1983 TV series)|1980s ''Alvin'' cartoons]] for his role in the film.<ref name = \"seventeen\">{{cite web|last=Eisinger|first=Amy|date=March 20, 2008|url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/q-and-a/a1779/jesse-mccartney-qa-chipmunks/|title=Jesse McCartney|work=[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]]|accessdate=December 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Alvin and the Chipmunks'' project began filming on March 28, 2007,<ref>{{cite web|last=Grove|first=Chris|date=March 8, 2007|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/features/earl-meets-the-chipmunks/|title=Earl Meets the Chipmunks|work=[[Animation Magazine]]|accessdate=December 24, 2019}}</ref> making it the first film to be produced under the leadership of [[20th Century Fox Animation|Fox Animation]] president Vanessa Morrison.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sperling|first=Nicole|date=March 8, 2007|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/alvin-lee-pops-chipmunks-131572|title=Alvin!!!!! Lee pops for 'Chipmunks'|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=December 24, 2019}}</ref> Seville's house was built on [[Sunset Gower Studios]] and contains references to Bagdasarian Sr.'s life. The set pieces included an [[upright piano]] he used to write his songs and a flower visual he painted; the house's address number includes 1958, the year he created the chipmunk characters; and the house design is based on a cottage built in 1919, the year Bagdasarian Sr. was born.<ref name = \"LAtimespro\">{{cite web|last=Rosen|first=Lisa|date=November 4, 2007|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2007-nov-04-ca-alvin4-story.html|title=Out of thin air|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=December 27, 2019}}</ref> In shots where Lee interacted with the chipmunks, the actor rehearsed with small stuffed animals indicating where the chipmunks would be; the animals were then removed when it was time to shoot, and he used his memory of where the animals were.<ref name = \"AWN\"/> \n\nThe chipmunks were animated by [[Rhythm and Hues Studios]], a company that previously animated creatures for projects such as ''[[Mouse Hunt]]'' (1997); ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe]]'' (2005); and ''[[Babe (film)|Babe]]'' (1995), which garnered Rhythm & Hues an [[Academy Award]].<ref name = \"AWN\">{{cite web|last=Wolff|first=Ellen|date=December 14, 2007|url=https://www.awn.com/vfxworld/alvin-and-chipmunks-critter-christmas|title='Alvin and the Chipmunks': A Critter Christmas|website=[[Animation World Network]]|accessdate=December 24, 2019}}</ref> As with all of its past projects, Rhythm & Hues used its own software for animating ''Alvin and the Chipmunks'', such as Voodoo and Icy, which was used for placing the CGI into live-action shots;<ref name = \"AWN\"/> although [[Autodesk]] programs like [[Autodesk Flame|Flame]] and [[Autodesk Maya|Maya]] were used.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ball|first=Ryan|date=December 21, 2007|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/vfx/autodesk-behind-holiday-blockbusters/|title=Autodesk Behind Holiday Blockbusters|work=Animation Magazine|accessdate=December 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Bagdasarian Jr., getting the look of the chipmunks suited for a live-action setting while maintaining the essence of the cartoon designs was challenging, and it took until September 10, 2006 for the artists to get it right.<ref>{{cite web|last=Garfinkel|first=Jacki|date=September 11, 2006|url=https://www.mediavillage.com/article/alvin-simon-and-theodore-are-coming-back/|title=Alvin, Simon and Theodore are Coming Back|website=Media Village|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref> Hill instructed the artists to make the chipmunks look realistic, but not entirely like chipmunks.<ref name = \"AWN\"/> In addition to observing real chipmunks offered by [[Universal Studios]], Rhythm and Hues studied all versions of the chipmunk characters from past ''Alvin'' media for conceiving, fur-texturing, and animating designs for the film.<ref name = \"AWN\"/> Human dancers were referenced for animating the dance movements of the chipmunks, and [[YouTube]] videos of famous guitarists playing the guitar influenced how Alvin's guitar-playing was animated.<ref name = \"AWN\"/> [[High-dynamic-range images]] of sets were also used for lighting the chipmunks to fit the live-action shots.<ref name = \"AWN\"/> The most difficult part of integrating the CGI critters in the live-action shots was [[match moving]] for instances when they climb on Seville's head.<ref name = \"AWN\"/> For scenes where the chipmunks interacted with props, some of them were live-action props while others, such as a paper airplane, were produced and animated with computers.<ref name = \"AWN\"/>\n\n== Release ==\nThe first poster for ''Alvin and the Chipmunks'' was revealed online on July 4, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/21742-here-are-alvin-and-the-chipmunks|title=Here are Alvin and the Chipmunks|website=ComingSoon.net|date=July 4, 2007|accessdate=December 27, 2019}}</ref> Later that month, Fox launched the official website for ''Alvin and the Chipmunks'' with only a trailer and synopsis;<ref>{{cite web|last=Strowbridge|first=C.S.|date=July 29, 2007|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/news/175510830-Movie-Website-Updates-for-July-22-July-28-2007|title=Movie Website Updates for July 22 \u2013 July 28, 2007|work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=December 24, 2019}}</ref> Several games were added later on.<ref>{{cite web|last=Strowbridge|first=C.S.|date=December 15, 2007|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/news/178740830-Movie-Website-Reviews-for-Weekend-of-December-15-2007|title=Movie Website Reviews for Weekend of December 15, 2007|website=The Numbers|accessdate=December 24, 2019}}</ref> In an August 2007 survey of 750 American teens ran by [[eCRUSH]] and OTX, ''Alvin and the Chipmunks'', alongside ''[[Saw IV]]'', ''[[National Treasure: Book of Secrets]]'', ''[[Mama's Boy]]'', ''[[Fred Claus]]'', ''[[I Am Legend (film)|I Am Legend]]'', and ''[[Enchanted (film)|Enchanted]]'', were the most anticipated films of the 2007 fall and winter seasons in the group.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schiller|first=Gail|date=August 27, 2007|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/study-tv-trailers-keep-teens-148820|title=Study: TV, trailers keep teens tuned to movies|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=December 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nInternationally, ''Alvin and the Chipmunks'' was released in Jamaica and the Lesser Antilles on December 12, 2007;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl354452993/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Jamaica)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1914734081/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Lesser Antilles)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref> Greece, Hong Kong, Malaysia, Puerto Rico, and Singapore on December 13, 2007;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl471893505/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Greece)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl505447937/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Hong Kong)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl253789697/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Malaysia)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl119571969/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Puerto Rico)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl2116060673/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Singapore)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref> Iceland, Romania, and Turkey on December 14, 2007;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl320898561/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Iceland)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl2065729025/weekly/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Romania)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1948288513/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Turkey)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref> Bahrain, Belgium, France, Jordan, Oman, South Korea, and Switzerland on December 19, 2007;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl723551745/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Bahrain)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl706774529/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Belgium)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl455116289/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (France)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl371230209/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Jordan)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl52463105/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Oman)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl153126401/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (South Africa)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1897956865/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Switzerland)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref> Chile, the Czech Republic, Germany, Hungary, Lebanon, Kuwait, Portugal, Qatar, Russia, Slovakia, Thailand, Ukraine, and the United Arab Emirates on December 20, 2007;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl555779585/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Chile)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl572556801/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Czech Republic)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl790660609/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Czech Republic/Slovakia)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl589334017/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Germany)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl270566913/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Hungary)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl169903617/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Kuwait)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl186680833/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Lebanon)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl2015397377/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Portugal)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl2032174593/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Qatar)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl2048951809/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Russia/CIS)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1931511297/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Thailand)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1998620161/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Ukraine)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1746961921/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (United Arab Emirates)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref> Austria, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, Mexico, Spain, United Kingdom, and Venezuela on December 21, 2007;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl673220097/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Austria)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl656442881/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Estonia)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl220235265/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Latvia)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl203458049/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Lithuania)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl237012481/weekend/|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (Mexico)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite 