 the divine secrets inscribed in forgotten runes. Like other leaders, they heal and buff their allies. More importantly, they gain secondary effects to all of their powers depending on which rune state they are in. || ''Player's Handbook 3''\n|-\n| Seeker<ref name=\"SeekerDragonPreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wizards.com/dnd/Article.aspx?x=dnd/drfe/20091006|archive-date=January 7, 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20100107154527/http://www.wizards.com/dnd/Article.aspx?x=dnd/drfe/20091006|title=The Seeker: Player's Handbook 3 Debut Content!|access-date=November 1, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> || Controller<ref name=\"SeekerDragonPreview\"/> || Defender or Striker || Primal<ref name=\"SeekerDragonPreview\"/> || Versed in hunting techniques handed down through the generations, seekers combine thrown weapon and bow techniques with primal evocations. The combination allows seekers great range in which to deliver deadly attacks that confound and hamper their enemies. || ''Player's Handbook 3'' <ref name=\"SeekerDragonPreview\"/>\n|-\n| [[Shaman (Dungeons & Dragons)|Shaman]]<ref name=\"ShamanPreview\">[http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dnd/drfe/20090202]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214214517/http://wizards.com/default.asp?x=dnd%2Fdrfe%2F20090202 |date=February 14, 2009 }}</ref> || Leader<ref name=\"ShamanPreview\"/> || Defender or Striker<ref name=\"ShamanPreview\"/> || Primal<ref name=\"ShamanPreview\"/> || Shamans gather spirits to intervene in the material world, healing their allies and disabling their foes. These spirits group under grand marshals like the World Serpent, tied to specific abilities. || ''Player's Handbook 2'' <ref>{{cite book|title=Player's Handbook 2 - Shaman Power Cards: A 4th Edition D&D Accessory|first=Wizards RPG|last=Team|date=August 18, 2009|publisher=Wizards of the Coast|isbn = 978-0786952885}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Sorcerer (Dungeons & Dragons)|Sorcerer]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forums.gleemax.com/showthread.php?t=1031661|title=Homepage|website=Wizards Corporate|access-date=June 6, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090301081744/http://forums.gleemax.com/showthread.php?t=1031661|archive-date=March 1, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"sorcerer 1-3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dnd/drfe/20090126|title=The Sorcerer, Levels 1-3|website=Forums.gleemax.com|accessdate=17 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090921093422/http://wizards.com/default.asp?x=dnd%2Fdrfe%2F20090126|archive-date=September 21, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> || Striker<ref name=\"sorcerer 1-3\"/> || Controller<ref name=\"sorcerer 1-3\"/> || Arcane<ref name=\"sorcerer 1-3\"/> || Sorcerers are wielders of raw arcane power. Where a wizard wields magic like a fighter wields a sword, a sorcerer wields magic like a barbarian swinging a greataxe. The magic they use is hardly controlled and may have some chaotic side effects.  || ''Player's Handbook 2''\n|-\n| Swordmage || Defender<ref name=\"SwordmageExcerpt\">[http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dnd/4ex/20080826a]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205063235/http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dnd%2F4ex%2F20080826a |date=December 5, 2008 }}</ref> || None<ref name=\"SwordmageExcerpt\" /> || Arcane<ref name=\"SwordmageExcerpt\" /> || The sword is used as an arcane focus for the swordmage's abilities, including [[aegis]]es of shielding, ensaring, and attacking. They ward themselves and enchant their blades to combat any foe. || ''Forgotten Realms Player's Guide''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=products/dndacc/218587200|title=Forgotten Realms Player's Guide|website=Wizards.com|accessdate=17 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090902074125/http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=products%2Fdndacc%2F218587200|archive-date=September 2, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| Warden<ref>[http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x-dnd/drfe/20090105] {{dead link|date=January 2018|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> || Defender || Controller or Striker || Primal || The warden uses the power of the primal spirits to protect their allies. They are defenders of the wilderness and make moving around the battlefield very troublesome for their enemies. || ''Player's Handbook 2''<ref>{{cite book|title=Player's Handbook 2 - Warden Power Cards: A 4th Edition D&D Accessory|first=Wizards RPG|last=Team|date=August 18, 2009|publisher=Wizards of the Coast|isbn = 978-0786952892}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Multiclass-only classes===\nThese classes are only available through multiclassing. They cannot be chosen as a character's main class.\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n! Class || Role || Power source || Description || Sourcebook\n|-\n| Spellscarred<ref>[http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dnd/4pr/20080703a]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090726083909/http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dnd%2F4pr%2F20080703a |date=July 26, 2009 }}</ref> || None || Arcane || Those who were touched by the wild Spellplague may have developed a spellscar. The spellscar manifests as wild lines of blue that may ignite when the subject is under the effect of a certain emotion. They can bestow weird magical powers but a small few attempt to master the gifts they bestow. || ''Forgotten Realms Player's Guide''\n|}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n\n==5th edition==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n! Class || Role || Power source || Description || Sourcebook\n|-\n| Artificer<ref>[https://dnd.wizards.com/products/tabletop-games/rpg-products/eberron]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127184804/https://dnd.wizards.com/products/tabletop-games/rpg-products/eberron|date=November 27, 2019 }}</ref> || None || Arcane || . || ''[[Eberron: Rising from the Last War]]''\n|}\n\nThe ''Dungeon Master's Guide'' contains alternate class options for the Cleric and Paladin (the Death domain and the Oathbreaker, respectively),<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mearls|first1=Mike|last2=Crawford|first2=Jeremy|title=Dungeon Master's Guide|date=December 2014|isbn=978-0-7869-6562-5|pages=96\u201397|edition= 5th}}</ref> while accessory books ''Sword Coast Adventurer's Guide'' and ''Xanathar's Guide to Everything'' contain multiple additional subclasses for the base classes in the ''Player's Handbook'' in keeping with the fifth edition's use of such archetypes to vary classes.\n\nMany of these were introduced as playtests in the article series \"Unearthed Arcana\" on the Wizards of the Coast web site.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Thompson|first1=Rodney|title=Modifying Classes|url=http://dnd.wizards.com/articles/features/modifying-classes|website=Dungeons & Dragons|publisher=Wizards of the Coast|accessdate=July 27, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728110246/http://dnd.wizards.com/articles/features/modifying-classes|archive-date=July 28, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Mearls|first1=Mike|title=Unearthed Arcana: Waterborne Adventures|url=http://dnd.wizards.com/articles/features/unearthed-arcana-waterborne-adventures|website=Dungeons & Dragons|publisher=Wizards of the Coast|accessdate=July 27, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150729002508/http://dnd.wizards.com/articles/features/unearthed-arcana-waterborne-adventures|archive-date=July 29, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Other \"Unearthed Arcana\" articles presented playtest versions of full classes, with rules for psionics for 5th edition as a class called the Mystic,<ref>{{cite web|title=Awakened Mystic|url=https://dnd.wizards.com/articles/features/awakened-mystic|website=Dungeons & Dragons|publisher=Wizards of the Coast|date=July 6, 2015|accessdate=July 27, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728095352/http://dnd.wizards.com/articles/features/awakened-mystic|archive-date=July 28, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Psionics and the Mystic \u2013 Take Two|url=https://dnd.wizards.com/articles/features/psionics-and-mystic-%E2%80%93-take-two|website=Dungeons & Dragons|publisher=Wizards of the Coast|date=February 1, 2016|accessdate=July 27, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201190641/http://dnd.wizards.com/articles/features/psionics-and-mystic-%E2%80%93-take-two|archive-date=February 1, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Mystic Class|url=https://dnd.wizards.com/articles/unearthed-arcana/mystic-class|website=Dungeons & Dragons|publisher=Wizards of the Coast|date=March 13, 2017|accessdate=July 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701001917/https://dnd.wizards.com/articles/unearthed-arcana/mystic-class|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and a 5th edition version of the Artificer class, which has gone through multiple revisions. The Artificer originally appeared as a Wizard subclass in the very first \"Unearthed Arcana\" article in February 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dnd.wizards.com/articles/unearthed-arcana/unearthed-arcana-eberron|title=Unearthed Arcana: Eberron|website=Dungeons & Dragons|publisher=Wizards of the Coast|date=February 2, 2015|accessdate=July 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630212250/https://dnd.wizards.com/articles/unearthed-arcana/unearthed-arcana-eberron|archive-date=June 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and first appeared as a standalone class in a January 2017 article.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dnd.wizards.com/articles/unearthed-arcana/artificer|title=Unearthed Arcana: Artificer|website=Dungeons & Dragons|publisher=Wizards of the Coast|date=January 9, 2017|accessdate=October 26, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026214404/http://dnd.wizards.com/articles/unearthed-arcana/artificer|archive-date=October 26, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It was then revised and appeared with 2 initial subclasses in another \"Unearthed Arcana\" article in February 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dnd.wizards.com/articles/unearthed-arcana/artificer-revisited|title=Unearthed Arcana: The Artificer Revisited|website=Dungeons & Dragons|publisher=Wizards of the Coast|date=February 28, 2019|accessdate=March 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327091147/http://dnd.wizards.com/articles/unearthed-arcana/artificer-revisited|archive-date=March 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and another installment in May republished the content from February but included additional subclasses, spells, and infusions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dnd.wizards.com/articles/unearthed-arcana/artificer-returns|title=Unearthed Arcana: The Artificer Returns|website=Dungeons & Dragons|publisher=Wizards of the Coast|date=May 14, 2019|accessdate=July 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810044957/https://dnd.wizards.com/articles/unearthed-arcana/artificer-returns|archive-date=August 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> {{As of|2019|07}},  neither the Mystic nor the Artificer has been made official. However, lead rules designer [[Jeremy Crawford]] confirmed in a July 24, 2019, livestream that the Artificer would be revised based on feedback and then appear in an [[Eberron]] hardcover book scheduled for release in 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twitch.tv/videos/457439620|title=Dragon+ w/ Bart Carroll 1PM PT|website=Twitch|publisher=Wizards of the Coast|date=July 24, 2019|accessdate=July 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725074010/https://www.twitch.tv/videos/457439620|archive-date=July 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://comicbook.com/gaming/2019/05/20/dungeons-and-dragons-eberron-hardcover-2019/ |title='Dungeons & Dragons' to Release Eberron Hardcover in 2019 |last=Hoffer |first=Christian |date=May 20, 2019 |website=ComicBook.com |language=en |access-date=July 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725074010/https://comicbook.com/gaming/2019/05/20/dungeons-and-dragons-eberron-hardcover-2019/ |archive-date=July 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and later confirmed on Twitter that the class would also appear in the ''[[Wayfinder's Guide to Eberron]]'' digital product as previously planned.<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1154155211620884485 |user=JeremyECrawford |last=Crawford |first=Jeremy |date=July 24, 2019 |title=We still plan to add the artificer to the Wayfinder's Guide. |access-date=July 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{D&D topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alternative Dungeons and Dragons Classes, List Of}}\n[[Category:Dungeons & Dragons character classes| ]]\n", "name_user": "User0x539", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther sourcebooks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_alternative_Dungeons_%26_Dragons_classes"}
{"title_page": "Battle royale game", "text_new": "{{short description|Video game genre with the last-man-standing gameplay}}\n{{About|the video game genre|the narrative genre|Battle royale genre|other uses|Battle royale (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{VG Action}}\nA '''battle royale game''' is an [[Online game|online]] [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] [[video game genre]] that blends the survival, exploration, and scavenging elements of a [[survival game]] with [[Last man standing (gaming)|last-man-standing]] gameplay. Battle royale games involve dozens to hundreds of players, who start with minimal equipment and then must eliminate all other opponents while avoiding being trapped outside of a shrinking \"safe area\", with the winner being the last player or team alive. The name for the genre is taken from the 2000 Japanese film ''[[Battle Royale (film)|Battle Royale]]'', itself based on the [[Battle Royale (novel)|novel of the same name]], which presents a [[Battle royale genre|similar theme]] of a last-man-standing competition in a shrinking play zone.\n\nThe genre's origins arose from [[mod (video gaming)|mods]] for large-scale online survival games like ''[[Minecraft]]'' and ''[[ARMA 2]]'' in the early 2010s. By the end of the decade, the genre became a cultural phenomenon, with standalone games such as ''[[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]]'' (2017), ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]'' (2017) and ''[[Apex Legends]]'' (2019), each having received tens of millions of players within months of their releases.\n\n==Concept==\nBattle royale games are played between many individual players, pairs of two players or a number of small squads (typically of 3-5 players). In each match, the goal is to be the [[Last man standing (gaming)|last player or team standing]] by eliminating all other opponents. A match starts by placing the player-characters into a large map space, typically by having all players skydive from a large aircraft within a brief time limit. The map may have random distribution or allow players to have some control of where they start. All players start with minimal equipment, giving no player an implicit advantage at the onset. Equipment, usually used for combat, survival or transport is randomly scattered around the map, often at landmarks on the map, such as within buildings in [[ghost town]]s. Players need to search the map for these items while avoid being killed by other players, who cannot be visually marked or distinguishable either on-screen or on the map, requiring the player to solely use their own eyes and ears to deduce their positions. Equipment from eliminated players can usually be looted as well. These games often include some mechanic to push opponents closer together as the game progresses, usually taking the form of a gradually shrinking safe zone, with players outside of the zone eventually being killed.\n\nTypically, battle royale contestants are only given one [[Life (gaming)|life]] to play; any players who die are not allowed to [[respawn]]. Games with team support may allow players to enter a temporary, near-death state once health is depleted, giving allies the opportunity to [[glossary of video game terms#revive|revive]] them before they give out or are finished off by an opponent. The match is over when only one player or team remains, and the game typically provides some type of reward, such as in-game currency used for cosmetic items, to all players based on how long they survived. The random nature of starting point, item placement, and safe area reduction enables the battle royale genre to challenge players to think and react quickly and improve strategies throughout the match as to be the last man/team standing. In addition to standalone games, the battle royale concept may also be present as part of one of many game modes within a larger game, or may be applied as a user-created [[mod (video gaming)|mod]] created for another game.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/the-best-battle-royale-games-modes-and-mods/ | title = The best battle royale games, modes and mods | first = Fraser | last = Brown | date = September 15, 2017 | accessdate = September 15, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170915204216/http://www.pcgamer.com/the-best-battle-royale-games-modes-and-mods/ | archivedate = September 15, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere are various modifications that can be implemented atop the fundamentals of the battle royale. For example, ''[[Fortnite]]'' introduced a temporary mode in an event which is 50-versus-50 player mode in its ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]'' free-to-play game; players are assigned one of the two teams, and work with their teammates to collect resources and weapons towards constructing fortifications as the safe area of the game shrinks down, with the goal to eliminate all the players on the other team.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2017/12/7/16748276/fortnite-battle-royale-50-vs-50-trailer-date-tga-2017 | title = Fortnite: Battle Royale gets a new 50-versus-50 team mode | first = Charlie | last = Hall | date = December 7, 2017 | accessdate = December 12, 2017 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171213010918/https://www.polygon.com/2017/12/7/16748276/fortnite-battle-royale-50-vs-50-trailer-date-tga-2017 | archivedate = December 13, 2017| df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Early games (2012\u20132016)===\nFormulative elements of the battle royale genre had existed prior the 2010s. Gameplay modes featuring [[Last man standing (gaming)|last man standing]] rules has been a frequent staple of multiplayer online action games though generally with fewer total players as early as 1990's ''[[Bomberman (1990 video game)|Bomberman]]'' which introduced multiplayer game modes, with players, all starting with the same minimal abilities, collected power ups and fought until the last players was left standing.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-10-17-remembering-dyna-blaster-the-first-battle-royale-game-i-played | title = Remembering Dyna Blaster, the first Battle Royale game I played | first = Ian | last = Hagton | date = October 17, 2017 | accessdate = November 18, 2018 | work = [[Eurogamer]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190704154054/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-10-17-remembering-dyna-blaster-the-first-battle-royale-game-i-played | archive-date = July 4, 2019 | url-status = dead }}</ref> The elements of scavenging and surviving on a large open-world map were popularized through [[survival game]]s.<ref name=\"vg247\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2017/04/10/battle-royale-playerunknowns-battlegrounds-king-of-the-kill-and-the-new-genre-of-shooter/|title=Battle royale: PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds, King of the Kill and the new genre of shooter|website=VG247|first=Sherif|last=Saed|date=April 10, 2017|accessdate=June 9, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608191503/https://www.vg247.com/2017/04/10/battle-royale-playerunknowns-battlegrounds-king-of-the-kill-and-the-new-genre-of-shooter/|archivedate=June 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"pcgamer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-could-have-a-bright-future-in-the-battle-royale-genre-he-created/|title=Playerunknown's Battlegrounds could have a bright future in the battle royale genre he created|website=PC Gamer|first=Christopher|last=Livingston|date=February 28, 2017|accessdate=June 9, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617164755/http://www.pcgamer.com/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-could-have-a-bright-future-in-the-battle-royale-genre-he-created/|archivedate=June 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nShortly after the release of the 2012 film ''[[The Hunger Games (film)|The Hunger Games]]'', a server plug-in named Hunger Games (later changed to Survival Games) was developed for ''[[Minecraft]]''.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/blogs/technology-blog/minecraft-hunger-games-exists-just-amazing-imagining-165117705.html | title=Minecraft Hunger Games exists, and it's just as amazing as you're imagining | first=Mike | last=Wehner | date=May 15, 2012 | accessdate=September 24, 2017 | work=[[Yahoo! News]] | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924100233/https://www.yahoo.com/news/blogs/technology-blog/minecraft-hunger-games-exists-just-amazing-imagining-165117705.html | archivedate=September 24, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/battle-royale-games-explained/1100-6459225/ | title = Battle Royale Games Explained | first = Alessandro | last = Fillari | date = May 26, 2018 | accessdate = May 26, 2018 | work = [[GameSpot]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180526152403/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/battle-royale-games-explained/1100-6459225/ | archivedate = May 26, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Survival Games takes inspiration from the film, initially placing players at the center of the map near a set of equipment chests. When the game commences, players can compete over the central resources or spread out to find items stored in chests scattered around the play area. Players killed are eliminated and the last surviving player wins the match.<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=The Big Book of Minecraft |publisher=Triumph Books |page=70 |date=2014 |isbn=978-1-62937-028-6}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[DayZ (mod)|DayZ]]'', a [[mod (video gaming)|mod]] for ''[[ARMA 2]]'', released in August 2012, players struggle alongside or against each other to obtain basic necessities to continue living in a persistent [[sandbox game|sandbox]] filled with various dangers. These games were designed to include [[player versus player]] encounters, but generally these events were infrequent due to the size of the game's map and the persistence of the game world.<ref name=\"Hall\">{{Cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2017/9/22/16350170/pubg-fortnite-battle-royale-genre-opinion | title = PUBG and Fortnite's argument raises the question: Can you own a genre? | first = Charlie | last = Hall | date = September 22, 2017 | accessdate = September 22, 2017 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170923003827/https://www.polygon.com/2017/9/22/16350170/pubg-fortnite-battle-royale-genre-opinion | archivedate = September 23, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> This led to the development of game mods that sacrificed ''ARMA 2''/''DayZ'' open-endedness in favor of focusing on more frequent hostile interactions between players to determine an eventual winner.\n\nIn 2016, a battle royale [[mobile game]], ''[[Btooom!#Game|Btooom Online]]'', was developed and released in Japan. It was based on the 2009 [[manga]] ''[[Btooom]]'', which in turn was inspired by the Japanese film ''Battle Royale''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jeu vid\u00e9o : l'antique \" Bomberman \" a-t-il inspir\u00e9 les ph\u00e9nom\u00e8nes \" PUBG \" et \" Fortnite \" ? |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/pixels/article/2018/04/25/jeu-video-l-antique-bomberman-a-t-il-inspire-les-phenomenes-pubg-et-fortnite_5290540_4408996.html |accessdate=February 18, 2019 |work=[[Le Monde]] |date=April 25, 2018 |language=fr}}</ref> Despite some initial success on the Japanese mobile charts, ''Btooom Online'' became a commercial failure.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://goboiano.com/btooom-wont-get-a-2nd-season-as-mobile-game-flops/|title=Btooom! Won't Get a 2nd Season as Mobile Game Flops|last=Titsoff|first=Ader|date=April 5, 2017|work=GoBoiano|access-date=February 23, 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730181513/http://goboiano.com/btooom-wont-get-a-2nd-season-as-mobile-game-flops/|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Formation of standalone games (2017\u20132018)===\nWhile formative elements of the battle royale genre had been established before 2017, the genre was defined and grew out from two principal titles through 2017 and 2018: ''[[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]]'', followed by ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]''. Both games drew tens of millions of players in short periods of time, proving them as commercial successes and leading to future growth after 2018.\n\n''PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds'' was created by Brendan Greene, its title based on his online alias \"PlayerUnknown\". The game was based on a previous ''Battle Royale'' mod for ''ARMA 2''/''DayZ'' that first released in 2013.<ref name=\"pcgamer\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/insertcoin/2017/09/22/pubg-developer-calls-out-fortnite-for-copying-its-battle-royale-format/#659e2e767d2f|title='PUBG' Developer Unironically Calls Out 'Fortnite' For Copying Its Battle Royale Format|work=Forbes|date=September 22, 2017|first=Paul|last=Tassi|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015193311/https://www.forbes.com/sites/insertcoin/2017/09/22/pubg-developer-calls-out-fortnite-for-copying-its-battle-royale-format/#659e2e767d2f|archivedate=October 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/glixel/news/meet-playerunknown-creator-of-the-battle-royale-genre-w475728|title=Meet Brendan 'Playerunknown' Greene, Creator of the Twitch Hit 'Battlegrounds'|work=Rolling Stone|first=Luke|last=Winkie|date=April 7, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730075114/http://www.rollingstone.com/glixel/news/meet-playerunknown-creator-of-the-battle-royale-genre-w475728|archivedate=July 30, 2017}}</ref> This mod was directly inspired by the 2000 Japanese film ''[[Battle Royale (film)|Battle Royale]]'', which told the story of a number of students transported to an island and forced to battle each other to be the sole survivor, lending to the mod's name.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.playbattlegrounds.com/news/24.pu | title = INVEN Game Conference Talk | first = Brendan | last = Greene | date = February 15, 2017 | accessdate = June 8, 2017 | publisher = Playerunknown's Battlegrounds | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170610101755/http://playbattlegrounds.com/news/24.pu | archivedate = June 10, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> In Greene's case, to differ his offering from ''Hunger Games''-inspired mods, he designed the mod to randomly scatter weapons around the map instead of from a central repository. Greene updated this mode for ''[[ARMA 3]]'' when the ''DayZ'' team opted to release their game as a [[DayZ (video game)|standalone game]]. Greene continued to adopt his format as a consultant for ''[[H1Z1: King of the Kill]]'' before becoming the creative developer at [[Bluehole (company)|Bluehole]] of a standalone game representing his vision of the battle royale genre, ''[[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]]''. While ''Battlegrounds'' was not the first battle royale game, its release to [[early access]] in March 2017 drew a great deal of attention, selling over twenty million copies by the end of the year,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/pubg-reaches-a-big-sales-milestone-as-creator-prom/1100-6454752/ | title = PUBG Reaches A Big Sales Milestone As Creator Promises \"Change Is Coming\" | first = Chris | last = Pereira | date = November 7, 2017 | accessdate = November 7, 2017 | work = [[GameSpot]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://venturebeat.com/2017/12/15/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-sells-1-million-xbox-one-copies-in-3-days/ | title = PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds sells 1 million Xbox One copies in 3 days | first = Mike | last = Minotii | date = December 15, 2017 | accessdate = December 15, 2017 | work = [[Venture Beat]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171215220709/https://venturebeat.com/2017/12/15/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-sells-1-million-xbox-one-copies-in-3-days/ | archivedate = December 15, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and is considered the defining game of the genre.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.vg247.com/2017/04/10/battle-royale-playerunknowns-battlegrounds-king-of-the-kill-and-the-new-genre-of-shooter/ | title = Battle royale: PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds, King of the Kill and the new genre of shooter | first = Sharif | last = Saed | date = April 10, 2017 | accessdate = July 27, 2017 | work = [[VG247]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170802162326/https://www.vg247.com/2017/04/10/battle-royale-playerunknowns-battlegrounds-king-of-the-kill-and-the-new-genre-of-shooter/ | archivedate = August 2, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> In September 2017, the game broke the previous record for highest number of concurrent players on Steam, with  over 1.3 million users playing the game simultaneously.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://plarium.com/en/mmo-games/battle-royale/ | title = How Battle Royale is changing online gaming | accessdate = February 27, 2018 | work = [[Plarium]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180228100725/https://plarium.com/en/mmo-games/battle-royale/ | archivedate = February 28, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''Battlegrounds''{{'}} explosive growth and how it established the battle royale genre was considered one of the top trends in the video game industry in 2017.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://business.financialpost.com/technology/gaming/the-year-in-games-5-news-stories-and-trends-that-dominated-the-industry-in-2017 | title = The year in games: Five news stories and trends that dominated the industry in 2017 | first = Chad | last = Sapieha | date = December 14, 2017 | accessdate = December 18, 2017 | work = [[National Post]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171215155814/http://business.financialpost.com/technology/gaming/the-year-in-games-5-news-stories-and-trends-that-dominated-the-industry-in-2017 | archivedate = December 15, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/311869/5_trends_that_defined_the_game_industry_in_2017.php | title = 5 trends that defined the game industry in 2017 | first = Kris | last = Graft | date = December 18, 2017 | accessdate = December 18, 2017 | work = [[Gamasutra]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171222052025/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/311869/5_trends_that_defined_the_game_industry_in_2017.php | archivedate = December 22, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPrior to and near ''Battlegrounds''{{'}} release, games from other developers took inspiration from highly played battle royale-style mods, as well as the popularity of [[The Hunger Games (film series)|''The Hunger Games'' film series]], which first premiered in 2012. ''[[Ark: Survival Evolved]]'' by Studio Wildcard introduced its \"Survival of the Fittest\" mode in July 2015, which was geared to be used for [[eSports]] tournaments. The mode was temporarily broken off as its own free-to-play game during 2016 before the developers opted to merge it back into the main game for ease of maintenance of the overall game.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/ark-survival-evolved-gets-a-survival-of-the-fittest-tournament-mode/ | title = Ark: Survival Evolved gets a \"Survival of the Fittest\" tournament mode | first = Andy | last = Chalk | date = July 24, 2015 | accessdate = September 22, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170923050929/http://www.pcgamer.com/ark-survival-evolved-gets-a-survival-of-the-fittest-tournament-mode/ | archivedate = September 23, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/08/02/ark-survival-of-the-fittest-not-f2p | title = Mod Me Up! Ark: Survival Of The Fittest No Longer F2P | first = Alice | last = O'Conner | date = August 2, 2016 | accessdate = September 22, 2017 | work = [[Rock Paper Shotgun]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170923193909/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/08/02/ark-survival-of-the-fittest-not-f2p/ | archivedate = September 23, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''Battlegrounds''{{'}} popularity created a new interest in the battle royale genre. Numerous games that copied the fundamental gameplay of ''Battlegrounds'' appeared in China, shortly after ''Battlegrounds''{{'}} release.<ref name=\"Livingston\">{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/pubg-exec-clarifies-objection-to-fortnite-battle-royale-its-not-about-the-idea-itself-its-about-epic-games/ | title = PUBG exec clarifies objection to Fortnite Battle Royale: 'it's not about the idea itself, it's about Epic Games' | first = Christopher | last = Livingston | date = September 23, 2017 | accessdate = September 23, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170923075730/http://www.pcgamer.com/pubg-exec-clarifies-objection-to-fortnite-battle-royale-its-not-about-the-idea-itself-its-about-epic-games/ | archivedate = September 23, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Epic Games]] had released ''[[Fortnite]]'', a cooperative survival game, into early access near the release of ''Battlegrounds''. Epic saw the potential to create their own battle royale mode, and by September 2017, released the free-to-play ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]'' which combined some of the survival elements and mechanics from the main ''Fortnite'' game with the Battle Royale gameplay concept.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-09-12-battle-royale-coming-to-fortnite-in-september | title = Battle Royale coming to Fortnite in September | first = Vic | last = Hood | date = September 12, 2017 | accessdate = September 12, 2017 | work = [[Eurogamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170912234406/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-09-12-battle-royale-coming-to-fortnite-in-september | archivedate = September 12, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-09-20-pubg-inspired-fornite-battle-royale-will-launch-as-a-free-standalone-game | title = PUBG-inspired Fortnite Battle Royale will launch as a free standalone game | first = Vic | last = Hood | date = September 20, 2017 | accessdate = September 20, 2017 | work = [[Eurogamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170921001323/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-09-20-pubg-inspired-fornite-battle-royale-will-launch-as-a-free-standalone-game | archivedate = September 21, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The game saw similar player counts as ''Battlegrounds'', with twenty million unique players reported by Epic Games by November 2017.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/fortnite-passes-20-million-players-big-new-patch-a/1100-6454776/ | title = Fortnite Passes 20 Million Players, Big New Patch Announced | first = Eddie | last = Makuch | date = November 7, 2017 | accessdate = November 8, 2017 | work = [[GameSpot]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171108205800/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/fortnite-passes-20-million-players-big-new-patch-a/1100-6454776/ | archivedate = November 8, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Bluehole expressed concern at this move, less due to being a clone of ''Battlegrounds'', but more so that they had been working with Epic Games for technical support of the [[Unreal Engine]] in ''Battlegrounds'', and thus they were worried that ''Fortnite'' may be able to include planned features to their battle royale mode before they could release those in ''Battlegrounds''.<ref name=\"Hall\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Skipper|first1=Ben|title=PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds team issues threat over 'carbon copy' battle royale mode in Epic Games' Fortnite|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-team-issues-threat-over-carbon-copy-battle-royale-mode-epic-games-1640468|website=[[International Business Times]]|accessdate=September 22, 2017|language=en|date=September 22, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922165952/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-team-issues-threat-over-carbon-copy-battle-royale-mode-epic-games-1640468|archivedate=September 22, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Livingston\"/> ''Battleground''{{'s}} developer, [[PUBG Corporation]], filed a lawsuit against Epic in South Korea in January 2018 claiming ''Fortnite Battle Royale'' infringements on ''Battlegrounds''{{'}} copyrights.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |title=Fortnite sued for 'copying' rival game |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-44287860 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=May 29, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180531053521/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-44287860 |archivedate=May 31, 2018  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-29/fortnite-versus-pubg-two-game-giants-are-set-to-battle-in-court | title = Most Popular Game on the Planet Accused of Copyright Violation | first1 = Yuji | last1 = Nakamura | first2 = Sam | last2 = Kim | date = May 29, 2018 | accessdate = May 29, 2018 | work = [[Bloomberg L.P.]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180530034851/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-29/fortnite-versus-pubg-two-game-giants-are-set-to-battle-in-court | archivedate = May 30, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Market observers predicted that there would be little likelihood of Bluehole winning the case, as it would be difficult to establish the originality of ''PUBG'' in court due to the battle royale game genre, which includes both ''PUBG'' and ''Fortnite Battle Royale'', being derived from the Japanese film ''Battle Royale''.<ref>{{cite news | title = Can PUBG win legal battle against Epic Games? | url = https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/tech/2018/06/134_250352.html | website = [[Korea Times]] | date = June 8, 2018 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180706082637/https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/tech/2018/06/134_250352.html | archivedate = July 6, 2018}}</ref> By the end of June 2018, the lawsuit had been closed by PUBG, under undisclosed reasons.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-27/pubg-drops-lawsuit-against-creators-of-gaming-phenom-fortnite | title = Copyright Lawsuit Dropped Against Fortnite Creators, Ending Legal Battle | first = Sam | last = Kim | date = June 26, 2018 | accessdate = June 27, 2018 | work = [[Bloomberg L.P.]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180627173422/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-27/pubg-drops-lawsuit-against-creators-of-gaming-phenom-fortnite | archivedate = June 27, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, ''Fortnite Battle Royale'' surpassed ''Battlegrounds'' in revenue,<ref name=pcgamesn>{{Cite web | url = https://www.pcgamesn.com/fortnite/fortnite-revenue | title = Fortnite made $126m in February, making more than PUBG for the first time | first = Ali | last = Jones | date = March 22, 2018 | accessdate = March 22, 2018 | work = [[PCGamesN]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180323030445/https://www.pcgamesn.com/fortnite/fortnite-revenue | archivedate = March 23, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> which was attributed to its [[free-to-play]] business model and [[cross-platform]] support, as well as its accessibility to [[Casual gaming|casual players]].<ref name=Verge/><ref name=\"Toms\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tomsguide.com/us/why-is-fortnite-so-popular,news-26921.html|title=Why Is Fortnite So Damn Popular \u2014 and Will It Last?|first=Michael|last=Andronico|date=April 6, 2018|accessdate=April 11, 2018|work=[[Tom's Guide]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411192449/https://www.tomsguide.com/us/why-is-fortnite-so-popular,news-26921.html|archivedate=April 11, 2018}}</ref> ''Battlegrounds'' creator Brendan Greene credited it with growing the battle royale genre.<ref name=Verge>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/3/23/17156952/pubg-creator-brendan-greene-epic-games-fortnite-battle-royale-genre-gdc-2018|title=PUBG creator says it's great Fortnite is growing the battle royale genre|first=Nick|last=Statt|date=March 23, 2018|accessdate=March 23, 2018|work=[[The Verge (website)|The Verge]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323211703/https://www.theverge.com/2018/3/23/17156952/pubg-creator-brendan-greene-epic-games-fortnite-battle-royale-genre-gdc-2018|archivedate=March 23, 2018}}</ref> Its mainstream publicity further increased following a stream by [[Tyler \"Ninja\" Blevins]] with [[Drake (musician)|Drake]], [[JuJu Smith-Schuster]] and [[Travis Scott]].<ref name=Engadget>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/03/17/fortnite-battle-royale-record-breaker/|title=The rise and rise (and rise) of 'Fortnite'|first=Matt|last=Brian|date=March 17, 2018|accessdate=March 23, 2018|work=[[Engadget]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324041607/https://www.engadget.com/2018/03/17/fortnite-battle-royale-record-breaker/|archivedate=March 24, 2018}}</ref> which set a [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] record for concurrent viewership.<ref name=\"poly_Drak\">{{Cite web| title = Drake sets records with his Fortnite: Battle Royale Twitch debut| author = Patrick Gill, Christopher Grant, Ross Miller, and Julia Alexander| work = Polygon| date = March 15, 2018| accessdate = March 19, 2018| url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/15/17123162/drake-ninja-fortnite-stream| url-status = live| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180315101436/https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/15/17123162/drake-ninja-fortnite-stream| archivedate = March 15, 2018| df = mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17143948/fortnite-ninja-drake-pornhub-yes-really | title = From Drake to porn, everyone wants a piece of Fortnite | first = Ben | last = Kuchera | date = March 20, 2018 | accessdate = March 20, 2018 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180320230606/https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17143948/fortnite-ninja-drake-pornhub-yes-really | archivedate = March 20, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> It accumulated a total playerbase of 45 million in January and 3.4 million concurrent players in February. [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] labeled it \"the biggest game of 2018\" and \"a genuine cultural phenomenon\",<ref name=\"Polygon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/fortnite-battle-royale/2018/3/30/17177068/why-is-fortnite-popular|title=Why is Fortnite Battle Royale so wildly popular?|first=Colin|last=Campbell|date=March 30, 2018|accessdate=April 11, 2018|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408060713/https://www.polygon.com/fortnite-battle-royale/2018/3/30/17177068/why-is-fortnite-popular|archivedate=April 8, 2018}}</ref> with \"everyone from NFL players to famous actors\" playing it,<ref name=Toms/> including [[Red Sox]] player [[Xander Bogaerts]] and [[Bayern Munich]]'s youth team borrowing celebrations from the game.<ref name=USA>{{cite web|url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2018/03/fortnite-is-taking-over-the-sports-world|title=Fortnite is taking over the sports world|first=Nick|last=Schwartz|date=March 31, 2018|accessdate=April 11, 2018|work=[[USA Today]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412082552/https://ftw.usatoday.com/2018/03/fortnite-is-taking-over-the-sports-world|archivedate=April 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOther popular battle royale games released in 2017, inspired by the success of ''PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds'', include two [[NetEase]] titles, ''[[Rules of Survival]]'' and [[mobile game]] ''Knives Out'', and the mobile game ''[[Garena Free Fire]]'' by [[Garena]]. Each of these games have received hundreds of millions of players, mostly in Asia, by 2018.<ref name=\"NetEase\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rulesofsurvivalgame.com|title=Rules of Survival|publisher=[[NetEase]]|access-date=2019-04-15|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030024643/http://www.rulesofsurvivalgame.com/|archivedate=October 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"gamasutra\">{{cite news |title=NetEase Games' Knives Out battlefield is spreading to PlayStation 4 |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/326197/NetEase_Games_Knives_Out_battlefield_is_spreading_to_PlayStation_4.php |work=[[Gamasutra]] |date=September 11, 2018 |access-date=October 28, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026222633/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/326197/NetEase_Games_Knives_Out_battlefield_is_spreading_to_PlayStation_4.php |archive-date=October 26, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"sensortower\"/>\n\n=== Mainstream popularity (2018\u2013present) ===\n\nWith the success of ''Battlegrounds'' and ''Fortnite'', the battle royale genre expanded greatly. Major publishers,{{r|livingston20191211}} including [[Electronic Arts]]<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/ea-responds-to-pubgs-massive-success-teases-new-an/1100-6456453/ | title = EA Responds To PUBG's Massive Success, Teases \"New And Innovative\" Modes For Its Own Games | first = Eddie | last = Makuch | date = January 30, 2018 | accessdate = May 17, 2018 | work = [[GameSpot]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180518055051/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/ea-responds-to-pubgs-massive-success-teases-new-an/1100-6456453/ | archivedate = May 18, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> [[Activision]],<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/activision-blizzard-battle-royale-1202799186/ | title = Activision Blizzard Not Worried About 'Fortnite' Competition | first = Stefanie | last = Fogel | date = May 4, 2018 | accessdate = May 17, 2018 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180517090407/http://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/activision-blizzard-battle-royale-1202799186/ | archivedate = May 17, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and [[Ubisoft]]<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/ubisoft-responds-to-fortnites-massive-popularity-t/1100-6459040/ | title = Ubisoft Responds To Fortnite's Massive Popularity, Teases It May Follow The Trend | first = Eddie | last = Makuch | date = May 17, 2018 | accessdate = May 17, 2018 | work = [[GameSpot]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180518033245/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/ubisoft-responds-to-fortnites-massive-popularity-t/1100-6459040/ | archivedate = May 18, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> acknowledged the impact of the growing genre and impact on their future plans. Activision's ''[[Call of Duty]]'' series features a battle royale mode titled Blackout in its 2018 installment, ''[[Call of Duty: Black Ops 4]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/call-of-duty-black-ops-4-has-a-battle-royale-mode/1100-6459017/|title=Call Of Duty: Black Ops 4 Has A Battle Royale Mode|last=Knezevic|first=Kevin|date=May 17, 2018|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|access-date=May 17, 2018}}</ref> as does EA's ''[[Battlefield V]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/battlefield-5-battle-royale-mode-dice-discusses-ho/1100-6459565/ | title = Battlefield 5 Battle Royale Mode: DICE Discusses How It Happened | first = Eddie | last = Makuch | date = June 11, 2018 | accessdate = June 11, 2018 | work = [[GameSpot]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180610091712/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/battlefield-5-battle-royale-mode-dice-discusses-ho/1100-6459565/ | archivedate = June 10, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Other established games added battle royale-inspired gamemodes in updates, such as ''[[Grand Theft Auto Online]]'',<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/gta-online-gets-a-pubg-style-battle-royale-mode-in-the-smugglers-run-update/ | title = GTA Online gets a PUBG-style Battle Royale mode in the Smuggler's Run update | first = Andy | last = Chalk | date = August 29, 2017 | accessdate = September 12, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170913043922/http://www.pcgamer.com/gta-online-gets-a-pubg-style-battle-royale-mode-in-the-smugglers-run-update/ | archivedate = September 13, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''[[Paladins (video game)|Paladins]]'',<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/hi-rez-president-explains-why-battlegrounds-name-was-chosen-for-paladins-new-mode/ | title = Hi-Rez president explains why 'Battlegrounds' name was chosen for Paladins' new mode | first = Joe | last = Donnelly | date = January 5, 2018 | accessdate = January 5, 2018 | work = [[PC Gamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180105233645/http://www.pcgamer.com/hi-rez-president-explains-why-battlegrounds-name-was-chosen-for-paladins-new-mode/ | archivedate = January 5, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''[[Dota 2]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stewart|first1=Sam|title=Dota 2 Is Getting a Battle Royale Game Mode|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/05/08/dota-2-is-getting-a-battle-royale-game-mode|website=IGN|accessdate=May 9, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509023603/http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/05/08/dota-2-is-getting-a-battle-royale-game-mode|archivedate=May 9, 2018|date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Battlerite]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wood|first1=Austin|title=MOBA brawler Battlerite is getting a battle royale mode|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/moba-brawler-battlerite-is-getting-a-battle-royale-mode/|website=PC Gamer|accessdate=May 9, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510115244/https://www.pcgamer.com/moba-brawler-battlerite-is-getting-a-battle-royale-mode/|archivedate=May 10, 2018|date=May 3, 2018}}</ref> and ''[[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-12-06-counter-strike-global-offensive-goes-free-to-play | title=  Counter-Strike: Global Offensive goes free-to-play | first = Rebekah | last = Valentine | date = December 6, 2018 | accessdate = December 6, 2018 | work = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] }}</ref> In February 2019, EA released the free-to-play ''[[Apex Legends]]'', which exceeded 50 million player accounts within a month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/03/apex_legends_reaches_50_million_players_in_its_first_month|title=Apex Legends Reaches 50 Million Players In Its First Month|last=Tailby|first=Stephen|work=Push Square|date=March 4, 2019|accessdate=March 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304142048/http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/03/apex_legends_reaches_50_million_players_in_its_first_month|archive-date=March 4, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe battle royale approach has also been used in games from genres not normally associated with shooter games. ''[[Tetris 99]]'' is a 2019 game released by [[Nintendo]] for the [[Nintendo Switch]] that has 99 players simultaneously competing in a game of ''Tetris''. Players can direct \"attacks\" on other players for each line they complete, attempting to remain the last player standing.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/13/18224020/tetris-99-battle-royale-nintendo-switch-fortnite | title = Tetris is now a battle royale game with Tetris 99 | first = Julia | last = Alexander | date = February 13, 2019 | accessdate = February 13, 2019 | work = [[The Verge]] }}</ref> [[Blizzard Entertainment]] added a battle royale-inspired \"Battlegrounds\" mode to its digital card game ''[[Hearthstone]]'', where eight players vie to win over the others through several rounds of [[Draft (sports)|drafting]] new cards and fighting in one-on-one events.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/353607/Why_the_Hearthstone_devs_wanted_to_make_an_auto_battler.php | title = Why the Hearthstone devs wanted to make an auto battler | first = Bryant | last= Francis | date = November 11, 2019 | accessdate = December 11, 2019  |work = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref> The racing game ''[[Forza Horizon 4]]'' from [[Playground Games]] added a battle royale mode called \"The Eliminator\" where players all start with the same car, but can gain upgrades by beating other players and discovering \"drops\" around the map.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-12-11-forza-horizon-4-is-getting-a-battle-royale-mode-called-the-eliminator | title = Forza Horizon 4 is getting a battle royale mode called The Eliminator | first = Matt | last = Wales | date = December 11, 2019 | accessdate= December 11, 2019 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref>\n\n{{asof|2019|12}} dozens of battle royale games have debuted but, similar to the [[MOBA]] genre, only two or three titles have maintained mainstream popularity at the same time. Other games and battle royale modes had briefly become popular before their concurrent player count dropped and players returned to ''Fortnite'' or ''Battlegrounds''; ''Apex Legends'' was the year's only new successful battle royale game.<ref name=\"livingston20191211\">{{Cite magazine |last=Livingston |first=Christopher |date=2019-12-11 |title=How battle royale changed the last decade of games (and the next one) |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/how-battle-royale-changed-the-last-decade-of-games-and-the-next-one/ |magazine=PC Gamer |language=en-US |access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref> In contrast to other multiplayer-only games, the large number of players typically involved in battle royale games generally require a large enough concurrent player base for matchmaking in a reasonable amount of time. ''[[The Culling (video game)|The Culling]]'', by Xaviant Studios, was released in early access in 2016, and was designed to be a [[Live streaming|streaming-friendly]] battle royale mode for 16 players.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/270158/Making_a_battle_royale_for_players_and_viewers_alike_in_The_Culling.php | title = Making a battle royale for players and viewers alike in The Culling | first = Joel | last = Couture | date = April 13, 2016 | accessdate = September 22, 2017 | work = [[Gamasutra]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170923095513/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/270158/Making_a_battle_royale_for_players_and_viewers_alike_in_The_Culling.php | archivedate = September 23, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> However, following the release of ''Battlegrounds'', ''The Culling'' lost much of its player base, and a few months after releasing the full version of the game, Xaviant announced they were ending further development on it to move onto other projects.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/development-of-the-culling-has-come-to-a-halt/ | title = Development of The Culling has come to a halt | first = Andy | last = Chalk | date = December 18, 2017 | accessdate = December 18, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171219041946/http://www.pcgamer.com/development-of-the-culling-has-come-to-a-halt/ | archivedate = December 19, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''[[Radical Heights]]'' by [[Boss Key Productions]] was launched in April 2018 but within two weeks had lost 80% of its player base.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.destructoid.com/radical-heights-seems-to-be-hemorrhaging-players-500768.phtml | title = Radical Heights seems to be hemorrhaging players | first = Peter | last= Glagowski | date = April 28, 2018 | accessdate = October 12, 2018 | work = [[Destructoid]] }}</ref> ''SOS'', a battle royale game released by Outpost Games in December 2017, had its player counts drop into the double-digits by May 2018, leading Outpost to announce the game's closure by November 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamer.com/sos-the-battle-royale-you-can-win-with-your-voice-is-closing-in-november/  |title = SOS, the battle royale you can win with your voice, is closing in November | first = Andy | last = Chalk | date = October 12, 2018 | access-date = October 12, 2018 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref> While several major battle royale announcements occurred at [[E3]] in 2018, only ''[[Fallout 76]]''{{'}}s battle royale mode appeared at the trade show in 2019.{{r|livingston20191211}}\n\nThe [[Chinese government]], through its Audio and Video and Numeral Publishing Association, stated in October 2017 that it will discourage its citizens from playing battle royale games as they deem them too violent, which \"deviates from the values of socialism and is deemed harmful to young consumers\", as translated by ''[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-30/world-s-hottest-pc-game-could-be-banned-in-china-due-to-violence | title = World's Hottest PC Game Could Get Locked Out of China | first = Lulu Yilun | last = Chen | date = October 29, 2017 | accessdate = October 31, 2017 | work = [[Bloomberg Businessweek]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171030091807/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-30/world-s-hottest-pc-game-could-be-banned-in-china-due-to-violence | archivedate = October 30, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Gaming publications in the west speculated that this would make it difficult or impossible to publish battle royale within the country.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamesn.com/playerunknown-battlegrounds/pubg-china | title = The Chinese government is discouraging the development of battle royale games | first = Ali | last = Jones | date = October 30, 2017 | accessdate = October 30, 2017 | work = [[PCGamesN]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171030185708/https://www.pcgamesn.com/playerunknown-battlegrounds/pubg-china | archivedate = October 30, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> In November 2017, PUBG Corporation announced its partnership with [[Tencent]]  to publish the game in China, making some changes in the game to \"make sure they accord with socialist core values, Chinese traditional culture and moral rules\" to satisfy Chinese regulations and censors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-11-22-tencent-to-publish-playerunknowns-battlegrounds-in-china |title=Tencent to publish PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds in China |first=Matthew |last=Handrahan |date=November 22, 2017 |accessdate=November 22, 2017 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044018/http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-11-22-tencent-to-publish-playerunknowns-battlegrounds-in-china |archivedate=December 1, 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{citation | url = https://www.vg247.com/2017/11/22/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-has-been-approved-in-china-with-a-few-changes/ | title = PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds has been approved in China, with a few changes | first = Marshall | last = Lemon | date = November 22, 2017 | accessdate = November 22, 2017 | work = [[VG247]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171122161352/https://www.vg247.com/2017/11/22/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-has-been-approved-in-china-with-a-few-changes/ | archivedate = November 22, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-tencent-videogames/tencent-to-bring-worlds-hottest-video-game-to-china-promises-socialist-values-idUSKBN1DM192?feedType=RSS&feedName=technologyNews | title = Tencent to bring world's hottest video game to China, promises socialist values | date = November 22, 2017 | accessdate = December 15, 2017 | newspaper = [[Reuters]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171216034938/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-tencent-videogames/tencent-to-bring-worlds-hottest-video-game-to-china-promises-socialist-values-idUSKBN1DM192?feedType=RSS&feedName=technologyNews | archivedate = December 16, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> However, during mid-2018, the Chinese government revamped how it reviewed and classified games that are to be published in China, and by December 2018, after the formation of the new Online Ethics Review Committee, several battle royale titles, including ''Fortnite'' and ''PUBG'', were listed as prohibited or must be withdrawn from play.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamesn.com/fortnite/fortnite-china-ban | title=  Fortnite, PUBG, and Paladins have reportedly been banned by the Chinese government | first = Ali | last = Jones | date = December 11, 2018 | accessdate = December 11, 2018 | work = [[PCGamesN]] }}</ref> Despite the concern that PUBG Corporation and Tencent were taking with Chinese release, many [[video game clone|clones]] of ''Battlegrounds'' have been released in China already, and created a new genre there called \"chicken-eating game\", named based on the congratulatory line  to the last player standing in ''Battlegrounds'', \"Winner winner chicken dinner!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/310581/Inside_the_PUBGfueled_rise_of_chicken_eating_games_in_China.php|title=Inside the PUBG-fueled rise of 'chicken eating games' in China|first=Alex|last=Wawro|date=November 28, 2017|access-date=December 18, 2017|work=[[Gamasutra]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171227122651/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/310581/Inside_the_PUBGfueled_rise_of_chicken_eating_games_in_China.php|archive-date=December 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nThe rapid growth and success of the battle royale genre has been attributed to several factors, including the way all players start in the same vulnerable state and eliminating any intrinsic advantage for players, and being well-suited for being a spectator eSport.<ref name=\"wired maslow\"/> Other factors including specific games' business models, such as ''Fortnite Battle Royale'' being free and available across computers, consoles, and mobile devices.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/05/21/how-fortnite-captured-teens-hearts-and-minds | title = How Fortnite Captured Teens' Hearts and Minds | first = Nick | last = Paumgarten | date = May 15, 2018 | accessdate = May 15, 2018 | work = [[The New Yorker]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180515040304/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/05/21/how-fortnite-captured-teens-hearts-and-minds | archivedate = May 15, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> A [[University of Utah]] professor also considers that battle royale games realize elements of [[Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs]], a scheme to describe human motivation, more-so than video games have in the past. While the lowest tiers of Maslow's hierarchy, physiological and safety, are met by the survival elements of battle royales, the love/belonging and esteem tiers are a result of the battle royale being necessarily a social and competitive game, and the final tier of self-actualization comes from becoming skilled in the game to win frequently.<ref name=\"wired maslow\">{{cite web | url = https://www.wired.com/story/fortnite-battlefield-rise-of-battle-royale/ | title = WHY BATTLE ROYALE GAMES LIKE FORTNITE ARE EVERYWHERE (IT'S NOT JUST MONEY) | first = Carter | last = Melrose | date = June 14, 2018 | accessdate = June 14, 2018 | work = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180615011914/https://www.wired.com/story/fortnite-battlefield-rise-of-battle-royale/ | archivedate = June 15, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n''[[Business Insider]]'' projected that battle royale games would bring in over {{USD|2 billion|long=no}} during 2018, and would grow to {{USD|20 billion|long=no}} in 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/07/20/analysts-predict-battle-royale-games-could-make-20-billion-next-year | title = Analysts Predict Battle Royale Games Could Make $20 Billion Next Year | first = Jessie | last = Wade | date = July 20, 2018 | accessdate = July 20, 2018 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref> SuperData Research reported that, [[2018 in video gaming|in 2018]], the three top-grossing battle royale games (''Fortnite'', ''PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds'' and ''Call of Duty: Black Ops 4'') generated nearly {{US$|4 billion|long=no}} in combined digital revenue.<ref>{{cite web |title=Market Brief {{ndash}} 2018 Digital Games & Interactive Entertainment Industry Year In Review |url=https://www.superdataresearch.com/market-data/market-brief-year-in-review/ |website=SuperData Research |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref> Sensor Tower reported that 2018's top three [[List of most-played mobile games by player count|most-downloaded mobile]] battle royale games (''[[PUBG Mobile]]'', ''[[Garena Free Fire]]'' and ''Fortnite'') received over 500{{nbsp}}million downloads combined that year.<ref name=\"sensortower\">{{cite web |title=Q4 and Full Year 2018: Store Intelligence Data Digest |url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/sensortower-itunes/Quarterly+Reports/Sensor-Tower-Q4-2018-Data-Digest.pdf |website=Sensor Tower  |date=January 16, 2019 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref> The [[List of most-played video games|most-played]] battle royale games include ''PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds'' with over 555{{nbsp}}million players,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Partleton |first1=Kayleigh |title=PUBG Mobile shoots through $1.5 billion in lifetime revenue |url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/asia/news/72145/pubg-mobile-1500000000-lifetime-revenue/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[Pocket Gamer]] |date=December 12, 2019}}</ref> [[NetEase]]'s mobile game ''Knives Out'' with over 250{{nbsp}}million players,<ref name=\"gamasutra\"/> ''Fortnite Battle Royale'' with nearly 250{{nbsp}}million players,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.engadget.com/2019/03/20/fortnite-250-million-epic-games-sweeney-interview-gdc/ | title = Epic Games has 250 million 'Fortnite' players and a lot of plans | first = Jessica | last = Conditt | date = March 20, 2019 | accessdate = March 20, 2019 | work = [[Engadget]] }}</ref> ''[[Rules of Survival]]'' with 230{{nbsp}}million players,<ref name=\"NetEase\"/> and ''Garena Free Fire'' with over 180{{nbsp}}million players.<ref name=\"sensortower\"/>\n\n[[Turtle Beach Corporation]], a manufacturer of headphones and microphones for gaming, reported an increase of over 200% in net revenues for the second quarter of 2018 over the same quarter in 2017, which they attributed to the popularity of the battle royale genre.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/323907/The_battle_royale_boom_helped_Turtle_Beach_achieve_a_record_quarter.php | title = The battle royale boom helped Turtle Beach achieve a record quarter | first=  Alissa | last =McAloon | date = August 7, 2018 | accessdate = August 7, 2018 | work = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Battle royal]]\n* [[Deathmatch]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Video game genre}}\n\n[[Category:Video game genres]]\n[[Category:Battle royale games| ]]\n[[Category:21st-century neologisms]]\n[[Category:2010s fads and trends]]\n[[Category:2020s fads and trends]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the video game genre|the narrative genre|Battle royale genre|other uses|Battle royale (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{VG Action}}\nA '''battle royale game''' is an [[Online game|online]] [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] [[video game genre]] that blends the survival, exploration, and scavenging elements of a [[survival game]] with [[Last man standing (gaming)|last-man-standing]] gameplay. Battle royale games involve dozens to hundreds of players, who start with minimal equipment and then must eliminate all other opponents while avoiding being trapped outside of a shrinking \"safe area\", with the winner being the last player or team alive. The name for the genre is taken from the 2000 Japanese film ''[[Battle Royale (film)|Battle Royale]]'', itself based on the [[Battle Royale (novel)|novel of the same name]], which presents a [[Battle royale genre|similar theme]] of a last-man-standing competition in a shrinking play zone.\n\nThe genre's origins arose from [[mod (video gaming)|mods]] for large-scale online survival games like ''[[Minecraft]]'' and ''[[ARMA 2]]'' in the early 2010s. By the end of the decade, the genre became a cultural phenomenon, with standalone games such as ''[[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]]'' (2017), ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]'' (2017) and ''[[Apex Legends]]'' (2019), each having received tens of millions of players within months of their releases.\n\n==Concept==\nBattle royale games are played between many individual players, pairs of two players or a number of small squads (typically of 3-5 players). In each match, the goal is to be the [[Last man standing (gaming)|last player or team standing]] by eliminating all other opponents. A match starts by placing the player-characters into a large map space, typically by having all players skydive from a large aircraft within a brief time limit. The map may have random distribution or allow players to have some control of where they start. All players start with minimal equipment, giving no player an implicit advantage at the onset. Equipment, usually used for combat, survival or transport is randomly scattered around the map, often at landmarks on the map, such as within buildings in [[ghost town]]s. Players need to search the map for these items while avoid being killed by other players, who cannot be visually marked or distinguishable either on-screen or on the map, requiring the player to solely use their own eyes and ears to deduce their positions. Equipment from eliminated players can usually be looted as well. These games often include some mechanic to push opponents closer together as the game progresses, usually taking the form of a gradually shrinking safe zone, with players outside of the zone eventually being killed.\n\nTypically, battle royale contestants are only given one [[Life (gaming)|life]] to play; any players who die are not allowed to [[respawn]]. Games with team support may allow players to enter a temporary, near-death state once health is depleted, giving allies the opportunity to [[glossary of video game terms#revive|revive]] them before they give out or are finished off by an opponent. The match is over when only one player or team remains, and the game typically provides some type of reward, such as in-game currency used for cosmetic items, to all players based on how long they survived. The random nature of starting point, item placement, and safe area reduction enables the battle royale genre to challenge players to think and react quickly and improve strategies throughout the match as to be the last man/team standing. In addition to standalone games, the battle royale concept may also be present as part of one of many game modes within a larger game, or may be applied as a user-created [[mod (video gaming)|mod]] created for another game.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/the-best-battle-royale-games-modes-and-mods/ | title = The best battle royale games, modes and mods | first = Fraser | last = Brown | date = September 15, 2017 | accessdate = September 15, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170915204216/http://www.pcgamer.com/the-best-battle-royale-games-modes-and-mods/ | archivedate = September 15, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere are various modifications that can be implemented atop the fundamentals of the battle royale. For example, ''[[Fortnite]]'' introduced a temporary mode in an event which is 50-versus-50 player mode in its ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]'' free-to-play game; players are assigned one of the two teams, and work with their teammates to collect resources and weapons towards constructing fortifications as the safe area of the game shrinks down, with the goal to eliminate all the players on the other team.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2017/12/7/16748276/fortnite-battle-royale-50-vs-50-trailer-date-tga-2017 | title = Fortnite: Battle Royale gets a new 50-versus-50 team mode | first = Charlie | last = Hall | date = December 7, 2017 | accessdate = December 12, 2017 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171213010918/https://www.polygon.com/2017/12/7/16748276/fortnite-battle-royale-50-vs-50-trailer-date-tga-2017 | archivedate = December 13, 2017| df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Early games (2012\u20132016)===\nFormulative elements of the battle royale genre had existed prior the 2010s. Gameplay modes featuring [[Last man standing (gaming)|last man standing]] rules has been a frequent staple of multiplayer online action games though generally with fewer total players as early as 1990's ''[[Bomberman (1990 video game)|Bomberman]]'' which introduced multiplayer game modes, with players, all starting with the same minimal abilities, collected power ups and fought until the last players was left standing.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-10-17-remembering-dyna-blaster-the-first-battle-royale-game-i-played | title = Remembering Dyna Blaster, the first Battle Royale game I played | first = Ian | last = Hagton | date = October 17, 2017 | accessdate = November 18, 2018 | work = [[Eurogamer]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190704154054/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-10-17-remembering-dyna-blaster-the-first-battle-royale-game-i-played | archive-date = July 4, 2019 | url-status = dead }}</ref> The elements of scavenging and surviving on a large open-world map were popularized through [[survival game]]s.<ref name=\"vg247\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2017/04/10/battle-royale-playerunknowns-battlegrounds-king-of-the-kill-and-the-new-genre-of-shooter/|title=Battle royale: PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds, King of the Kill and the new genre of shooter|website=VG247|first=Sherif|last=Saed|date=April 10, 2017|accessdate=June 9, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608191503/https://www.vg247.com/2017/04/10/battle-royale-playerunknowns-battlegrounds-king-of-the-kill-and-the-new-genre-of-shooter/|archivedate=June 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"pcgamer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-could-have-a-bright-future-in-the-battle-royale-genre-he-created/|title=Playerunknown's Battlegrounds could have a bright future in the battle royale genre he created|website=PC Gamer|first=Christopher|last=Livingston|date=February 28, 2017|accessdate=June 9, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617164755/http://www.pcgamer.com/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-could-have-a-bright-future-in-the-battle-royale-genre-he-created/|archivedate=June 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nShortly after the release of the 2012 film ''[[The Hunger Games (film)|The Hunger Games]]'', a server plug-in named Hunger Games (later changed to Survival Games) was developed for ''[[Minecraft]]''.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/blogs/technology-blog/minecraft-hunger-games-exists-just-amazing-imagining-165117705.html | title=Minecraft Hunger Games exists, and it's just as amazing as you're imagining | first=Mike | last=Wehner | date=May 15, 2012 | accessdate=September 24, 2017 | work=[[Yahoo! News]] | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924100233/https://www.yahoo.com/news/blogs/technology-blog/minecraft-hunger-games-exists-just-amazing-imagining-165117705.html | archivedate=September 24, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/battle-royale-games-explained/1100-6459225/ | title = Battle Royale Games Explained | first = Alessandro | last = Fillari | date = May 26, 2018 | accessdate = May 26, 2018 | work = [[GameSpot]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180526152403/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/battle-royale-games-explained/1100-6459225/ | archivedate = May 26, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Survival Games takes inspiration from the film, initially placing players at the center of the map near a set of equipment chests. When the game commences, players can compete over the central resources or spread out to find items stored in chests scattered around the play area. Players killed are eliminated and the last surviving player wins the match.<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=The Big Book of Minecraft |publisher=Triumph Books |page=70 |date=2014 |isbn=978-1-62937-028-6}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[DayZ (mod)|DayZ]]'', a [[mod (video gaming)|mod]] for ''[[ARMA 2]]'', released in August 2012, players struggle alongside or against each other to obtain basic necessities to continue living in a persistent [[sandbox game|sandbox]] filled with various dangers. These games were designed to include [[player versus player]] encounters, but generally these events were infrequent due to the size of the game's map and the persistence of the game world.<ref name=\"Hall\">{{Cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2017/9/22/16350170/pubg-fortnite-battle-royale-genre-opinion | title = PUBG and Fortnite's argument raises the question: Can you own a genre? | first = Charlie | last = Hall | date = September 22, 2017 | accessdate = September 22, 2017 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170923003827/https://www.polygon.com/2017/9/22/16350170/pubg-fortnite-battle-royale-genre-opinion | archivedate = September 23, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> This led to the development of game mods that sacrificed ''ARMA 2''/''DayZ'' open-endedness in favor of focusing on more frequent hostile interactions between players to determine an eventual winner.\n\nIn 2016, a battle royale [[mobile game]], ''[[Btooom!#Game|Btooom Online]]'', was developed and released in Japan. It was based on the 2009 [[manga]] ''[[Btooom]]'', which in turn was inspired by the Japanese film ''Battle Royale''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jeu vid\u00e9o : l'antique \" Bomberman \" a-t-il inspir\u00e9 les ph\u00e9nom\u00e8nes \" PUBG \" et \" Fortnite \" ? |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/pixels/article/2018/04/25/jeu-video-l-antique-bomberman-a-t-il-inspire-les-phenomenes-pubg-et-fortnite_5290540_4408996.html |accessdate=February 18, 2019 |work=[[Le Monde]] |date=April 25, 2018 |language=fr}}</ref> Despite some initial success on the Japanese mobile charts, ''Btooom Online'' became a commercial failure.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://goboiano.com/btooom-wont-get-a-2nd-season-as-mobile-game-flops/|title=Btooom! Won't Get a 2nd Season as Mobile Game Flops|last=Titsoff|first=Ader|date=April 5, 2017|work=GoBoiano|access-date=February 23, 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730181513/http://goboiano.com/btooom-wont-get-a-2nd-season-as-mobile-game-flops/|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Formation of standalone games (2017\u20132018)===\nWhile formative elements of the battle royale genre had been established before 2017, the genre was defined and grew out from two principal titles through 2017 and 2018: ''[[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]]'', followed by ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]''. Both games drew tens of millions of players in short periods of time, proving them as commercial successes and leading to future growth after 2018.\n\n''PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds'' was created by Brendan Greene, its title based on his online alias \"PlayerUnknown\". The game was based on a previous ''Battle Royale'' mod for ''ARMA 2''/''DayZ'' that first released in 2013.<ref name=\"pcgamer\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/insertcoin/2017/09/22/pubg-developer-calls-out-fortnite-for-copying-its-battle-royale-format/#659e2e767d2f|title='PUBG' Developer Unironically Calls Out 'Fortnite' For Copying Its Battle Royale Format|work=Forbes|date=September 22, 2017|first=Paul|last=Tassi|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015193311/https://www.forbes.com/sites/insertcoin/2017/09/22/pubg-developer-calls-out-fortnite-for-copying-its-battle-royale-format/#659e2e767d2f|archivedate=October 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/glixel/news/meet-playerunknown-creator-of-the-battle-royale-genre-w475728|title=Meet Brendan 'Playerunknown' Greene, Creator of the Twitch Hit 'Battlegrounds'|work=Rolling Stone|first=Luke|last=Winkie|date=April 7, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730075114/http://www.rollingstone.com/glixel/news/meet-playerunknown-creator-of-the-battle-royale-genre-w475728|archivedate=July 30, 2017}}</ref> This mod was directly inspired by the 2000 Japanese film ''[[Battle Royale (film)|Battle Royale]]'', which told the story of a number of students transported to an island and forced to battle each other to be the sole survivor, lending to the mod's name.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.playbattlegrounds.com/news/24.pu | title = INVEN Game Conference Talk | first = Brendan | last = Greene | date = February 15, 2017 | accessdate = June 8, 2017 | publisher = Playerunknown's Battlegrounds | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170610101755/http://playbattlegrounds.com/news/24.pu | archivedate = June 10, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> In Greene's case, to differ his offering from ''Hunger Games''-inspired mods, he designed the mod to randomly scatter weapons around the map instead of from a central repository. Greene updated this mode for ''[[ARMA 3]]'' when the ''DayZ'' team opted to release their game as a [[DayZ (video game)|standalone game]]. Greene continued to adopt his format as a consultant for ''[[H1Z1: King of the Kill]]'' before becoming the creative developer at [[Bluehole (company)|Bluehole]] of a standalone game representing his vision of the battle royale genre, ''[[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]]''. While ''Battlegrounds'' was not the first battle royale game, its release to [[early access]] in March 2017 drew a great deal of attention, selling over twenty million copies by the end of the year,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/pubg-reaches-a-big-sales-milestone-as-creator-prom/1100-6454752/ | title = PUBG Reaches A Big Sales Milestone As Creator Promises \"Change Is Coming\" | first = Chris | last = Pereira | date = November 7, 2017 | accessdate = November 7, 2017 | work = [[GameSpot]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://venturebeat.com/2017/12/15/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-sells-1-million-xbox-one-copies-in-3-days/ | title = PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds sells 1 million Xbox One copies in 3 days | first = Mike | last = Minotii | date = December 15, 2017 | accessdate = December 15, 2017 | work = [[Venture Beat]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171215220709/https://venturebeat.com/2017/12/15/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-sells-1-million-xbox-one-copies-in-3-days/ | archivedate = December 15, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and is considered the defining game of the genre.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.vg247.com/2017/04/10/battle-royale-playerunknowns-battlegrounds-king-of-the-kill-and-the-new-genre-of-shooter/ | title = Battle royale: PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds, King of the Kill and the new genre of shooter | first = Sharif | last = Saed | date = April 10, 2017 | accessdate = July 27, 2017 | work = [[VG247]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170802162326/https://www.vg247.com/2017/04/10/battle-royale-playerunknowns-battlegrounds-king-of-the-kill-and-the-new-genre-of-shooter/ | archivedate = August 2, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> In September 2017, the game broke the previous record for highest number of concurrent players on Steam, with  over 1.3 million users playing the game simultaneously.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://plarium.com/en/mmo-games/battle-royale/ | title = How Battle Royale is changing online gaming | accessdate = February 27, 2018 | work = [[Plarium]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180228100725/https://plarium.com/en/mmo-games/battle-royale/ | archivedate = February 28, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''Battlegrounds''{{'}} explosive growth and how it established the battle royale genre was considered one of the top trends in the video game industry in 2017.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://business.financialpost.com/technology/gaming/the-year-in-games-5-news-stories-and-trends-that-dominated-the-industry-in-2017 | title = The year in games: Five news stories and trends that dominated the industry in 2017 | first = Chad | last = Sapieha | date = December 14, 2017 | accessdate = December 18, 2017 | work = [[National Post]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171215155814/http://business.financialpost.com/technology/gaming/the-year-in-games-5-news-stories-and-trends-that-dominated-the-industry-in-2017 | archivedate = December 15, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/311869/5_trends_that_defined_the_game_industry_in_2017.php | title = 5 trends that defined the game industry in 2017 | first = Kris | last = Graft | date = December 18, 2017 | accessdate = December 18, 2017 | work = [[Gamasutra]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171222052025/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/311869/5_trends_that_defined_the_game_industry_in_2017.php | archivedate = December 22, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPrior to and near ''Battlegrounds''{{'}} release, games from other developers took inspiration from highly played battle royale-style mods, as well as the popularity of [[The Hunger Games (film series)|''The Hunger Games'' film series]], which first premiered in 2012. ''[[Ark: Survival Evolved]]'' by Studio Wildcard introduced its \"Survival of the Fittest\" mode in July 2015, which was geared to be used for [[eSports]] tournaments. The mode was temporarily broken off as its own free-to-play game during 2016 before the developers opted to merge it back into the main game for ease of maintenance of the overall game.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/ark-survival-evolved-gets-a-survival-of-the-fittest-tournament-mode/ | title = Ark: Survival Evolved gets a \"Survival of the Fittest\" tournament mode | first = Andy | last = Chalk | date = July 24, 2015 | accessdate = September 22, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170923050929/http://www.pcgamer.com/ark-survival-evolved-gets-a-survival-of-the-fittest-tournament-mode/ | archivedate = September 23, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/08/02/ark-survival-of-the-fittest-not-f2p | title = Mod Me Up! Ark: Survival Of The Fittest No Longer F2P | first = Alice | last = O'Conner | date = August 2, 2016 | accessdate = September 22, 2017 | work = [[Rock Paper Shotgun]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170923193909/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/08/02/ark-survival-of-the-fittest-not-f2p/ | archivedate = September 23, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''Battlegrounds''{{'}} popularity created a new interest in the battle royale genre. Numerous games that copied the fundamental gameplay of ''Battlegrounds'' appeared in China, shortly after ''Battlegrounds''{{'}} release.<ref name=\"Livingston\">{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/pubg-exec-clarifies-objection-to-fortnite-battle-royale-its-not-about-the-idea-itself-its-about-epic-games/ | title = PUBG exec clarifies objection to Fortnite Battle Royale: 'it's not about the idea itself, it's about Epic Games' | first = Christopher | last = Livingston | date = September 23, 2017 | accessdate = September 23, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170923075730/http://www.pcgamer.com/pubg-exec-clarifies-objection-to-fortnite-battle-royale-its-not-about-the-idea-itself-its-about-epic-games/ | archivedate = September 23, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Epic Games]] had released ''[[Fortnite]]'', a cooperative survival game, into early access near the release of ''Battlegrounds''. Epic saw the potential to create their own battle royale mode, and by September 2017, released the free-to-play ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]'' which combined some of the survival elements and mechanics from the main ''Fortnite'' game with the Battle Royale gameplay concept.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-09-12-battle-royale-coming-to-fortnite-in-september | title = Battle Royale coming to Fortnite in September | first = Vic | last = Hood | date = September 12, 2017 | accessdate = September 12, 2017 | work = [[Eurogamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170912234406/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-09-12-battle-royale-coming-to-fortnite-in-september | archivedate = September 12, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-09-20-pubg-inspired-fornite-battle-royale-will-launch-as-a-free-standalone-game | title = PUBG-inspired Fortnite Battle Royale will launch as a free standalone game | first = Vic | last = Hood | date = September 20, 2017 | accessdate = September 20, 2017 | work = [[Eurogamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170921001323/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-09-20-pubg-inspired-fornite-battle-royale-will-launch-as-a-free-standalone-game | archivedate = September 21, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The game saw similar player counts as ''Battlegrounds'', with twenty million unique players reported by Epic Games by November 2017.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/fortnite-passes-20-million-players-big-new-patch-a/1100-6454776/ | title = Fortnite Passes 20 Million Players, Big New Patch Announced | first = Eddie | last = Makuch | date = November 7, 2017 | accessdate = November 8, 2017 | work = [[GameSpot]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171108205800/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/fortnite-passes-20-million-players-big-new-patch-a/1100-6454776/ | archivedate = November 8, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Bluehole expressed concern at this move, less due to being a clone of ''Battlegrounds'', but more so that they had been working with Epic Games for technical support of the [[Unreal Engine]] in ''Battlegrounds'', and thus they were worried that ''Fortnite'' may be able to include planned features to their battle royale mode before they could release those in ''Battlegrounds''.<ref name=\"Hall\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Skipper|first1=Ben|title=PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds team issues threat over 'carbon copy' battle royale mode in Epic Games' Fortnite|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-team-issues-threat-over-carbon-copy-battle-royale-mode-epic-games-1640468|website=[[International Business Times]]|accessdate=September 22, 2017|language=en|date=September 22, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922165952/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-team-issues-threat-over-carbon-copy-battle-royale-mode-epic-games-1640468|archivedate=September 22, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Livingston\"/> ''Battleground''{{'s}} developer, [[PUBG Corporation]], filed a lawsuit against Epic in South Korea in January 2018 claiming ''Fortnite Battle Royale'' infringements on ''Battlegrounds''{{'}} copyrights.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |title=Fortnite sued for 'copying' rival game |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-44287860 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=May 29, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180531053521/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-44287860 |archivedate=May 31, 2018  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-29/fortnite-versus-pubg-two-game-giants-are-set-to-battle-in-court | title = Most Popular Game on the Planet Accused of Copyright Violation | first1 = Yuji | last1 = Nakamura | first2 = Sam | last2 = Kim | date = May 29, 2018 | accessdate = May 29, 2018 | work = [[Bloomberg L.P.]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180530034851/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-29/fortnite-versus-pubg-two-game-giants-are-set-to-battle-in-court | archivedate = May 30, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Market observers predicted that there would be little likelihood of Bluehole winning the case, as it would be difficult to establish the originality of ''PUBG'' in court due to the battle royale game genre, which includes both ''PUBG'' and ''Fortnite Battle Royale'', being derived from the Japanese film ''Battle Royale''.<ref>{{cite news | title = Can PUBG win legal battle against Epic Games? | url = https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/tech/2018/06/134_250352.html | website = [[Korea Times]] | date = June 8, 2018 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180706082637/https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/tech/2018/06/134_250352.html | archivedate = July 6, 2018}}</ref> By the end of June 2018, the lawsuit had been closed by PUBG, under undisclosed reasons.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-27/pubg-drops-lawsuit-against-creators-of-gaming-phenom-fortnite | title = Copyright Lawsuit Dropped Against Fortnite Creators, Ending Legal Battle | first = Sam | last = Kim | date = June 26, 2018 | accessdate = June 27, 2018 | work = [[Bloomberg L.P.]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180627173422/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-27/pubg-drops-lawsuit-against-creators-of-gaming-phenom-fortnite | archivedate = June 27, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, ''Fortnite Battle Royale'' surpassed ''Battlegrounds'' in revenue,<ref name=pcgamesn>{{Cite web | url = https://www.pcgamesn.com/fortnite/fortnite-revenue | title = Fortnite made $126m in February, making more than PUBG for the first time | first = Ali | last = Jones | date = March 22, 2018 | accessdate = March 22, 2018 | work = [[PCGamesN]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180323030445/https://www.pcgamesn.com/fortnite/fortnite-revenue | archivedate = March 23, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> which was attributed to its [[free-to-play]] business model and [[cross-platform]] support, as well as its accessibility to [[Casual gaming|casual players]].<ref name=Verge/><ref name=\"Toms\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tomsguide.com/us/why-is-fortnite-so-popular,news-26921.html|title=Why Is Fortnite So Damn Popular \u2014 and Will It Last?|first=Michael|last=Andronico|date=April 6, 2018|accessdate=April 11, 2018|work=[[Tom's Guide]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411192449/https://www.tomsguide.com/us/why-is-fortnite-so-popular,news-26921.html|archivedate=April 11, 2018}}</ref> ''Battlegrounds'' creator Brendan Greene credited it with growing the battle royale genre.<ref name=Verge>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/3/23/17156952/pubg-creator-brendan-greene-epic-games-fortnite-battle-royale-genre-gdc-2018|title=PUBG creator says it's great Fortnite is growing the battle royale genre|first=Nick|last=Statt|date=March 23, 2018|accessdate=March 23, 2018|work=[[The Verge (website)|The Verge]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323211703/https://www.theverge.com/2018/3/23/17156952/pubg-creator-brendan-greene-epic-games-fortnite-battle-royale-genre-gdc-2018|archivedate=March 23, 2018}}</ref> Its mainstream publicity further increased following a stream by [[Tyler \"Ninja\" Blevins]] with [[Drake (musician)|Drake]], [[JuJu Smith-Schuster]] and [[Travis Scott]].<ref name=Engadget>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/03/17/fortnite-battle-royale-record-breaker/|title=The rise and rise (and rise) of 'Fortnite'|first=Matt|last=Brian|date=March 17, 2018|accessdate=March 23, 2018|work=[[Engadget]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324041607/https://www.engadget.com/2018/03/17/fortnite-battle-royale-record-breaker/|archivedate=March 24, 2018}}</ref> which set a [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] record for concurrent viewership.<ref name=\"poly_Drak\">{{Cite web| title = Drake sets records with his Fortnite: Battle Royale Twitch debut| author = Patrick Gill, Christopher Grant, Ross Miller, and Julia Alexander| work = Polygon| date = March 15, 2018| accessdate = March 19, 2018| url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/15/17123162/drake-ninja-fortnite-stream| url-status = live| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180315101436/https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/15/17123162/drake-ninja-fortnite-stream| archivedate = March 15, 2018| df = mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17143948/fortnite-ninja-drake-pornhub-yes-really | title = From Drake to porn, everyone wants a piece of Fortnite | first = Ben | last = Kuchera | date = March 20, 2018 | accessdate = March 20, 2018 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180320230606/https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17143948/fortnite-ninja-drake-pornhub-yes-really | archivedate = March 20, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> It accumulated a total playerbase of 45 million in January and 3.4 million concurrent players in February. [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] labeled it \"the biggest game of 2018\" and \"a genuine cultural phenomenon\",<ref name=\"Polygon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/fortnite-battle-royale/2018/3/30/17177068/why-is-fortnite-popular|title=Why is Fortnite Battle Royale so wildly popular?|first=Colin|last=Campbell|date=March 30, 2018|accessdate=April 11, 2018|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408060713/https://www.polygon.com/fortnite-battle-royale/2018/3/30/17177068/why-is-fortnite-popular|archivedate=April 8, 2018}}</ref> with \"everyone from NFL players to famous actors\" playing it,<ref name=Toms/> including [[Red Sox]] player [[Xander Bogaerts]] and [[Bayern Munich]]'s youth team borrowing celebrations from the game.<ref name=USA>{{cite web|url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2018/03/fortnite-is-taking-over-the-sports-world|title=Fortnite is taking over the sports world|first=Nick|last=Schwartz|date=March 31, 2018|accessdate=April 11, 2018|work=[[USA Today]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412082552/https://ftw.usatoday.com/2018/03/fortnite-is-taking-over-the-sports-world|archivedate=April 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOther popular battle royale games released in 2017, inspired by the success of ''PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds'', include two [[NetEase]] titles, ''[[Rules of Survival]]'' and [[mobile game]] ''Knives Out'', and the mobile game ''[[Garena Free Fire]]'' by [[Garena]]. Each of these games have received hundreds of millions of players, mostly in Asia, by 2018.<ref name=\"NetEase\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rulesofsurvivalgame.com|title=Rules of Survival|publisher=[[NetEase]]|access-date=2019-04-15|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030024643/http://www.rulesofsurvivalgame.com/|archivedate=October 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"gamasutra\">{{cite news |title=NetEase Games' Knives Out battlefield is spreading to PlayStation 4 |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/326197/NetEase_Games_Knives_Out_battlefield_is_spreading_to_PlayStation_4.php |work=[[Gamasutra]] |date=September 11, 2018 |access-date=October 28, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026222633/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/326197/NetEase_Games_Knives_Out_battlefield_is_spreading_to_PlayStation_4.php |archive-date=October 26, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"sensortower\"/>\n\n=== Mainstream popularity (2018\u2013present) ===\n\nWith the success of ''Battlegrounds'' and ''Fortnite'', the battle royale genre expanded greatly. Major publishers,{{r|livingston20191211}} including [[Electronic Arts]]<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/ea-responds-to-pubgs-massive-success-teases-new-an/1100-6456453/ | title = EA Responds To PUBG's Massive Success, Teases \"New And Innovative\" Modes For Its Own Games | first = Eddie | last = Makuch | date = January 30, 2018 | accessdate = May 17, 2018 | work = [[GameSpot]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180518055051/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/ea-responds-to-pubgs-massive-success-teases-new-an/1100-6456453/ | archivedate = May 18, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> [[Activision]],<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/activision-blizzard-battle-royale-1202799186/ | title = Activision Blizzard Not Worried About 'Fortnite' Competition | first = Stefanie | last = Fogel | date = May 4, 2018 | accessdate = May 17, 2018 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180517090407/http://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/activision-blizzard-battle-royale-1202799186/ | archivedate = May 17, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and [[Ubisoft]]<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/ubisoft-responds-to-fortnites-massive-popularity-t/1100-6459040/ | title = Ubisoft Responds To Fortnite's Massive Popularity, Teases It May Follow The Trend | first = Eddie | last = Makuch | date = May 17, 2018 | accessdate = May 17, 2018 | work = [[GameSpot]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180518033245/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/ubisoft-responds-to-fortnites-massive-popularity-t/1100-6459040/ | archivedate = May 18, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> acknowledged the impact of the growing genre and impact on their future plans. Activision's ''[[Call of Duty]]'' series features a battle royale mode titled Blackout in its 2018 installment, ''[[Call of Duty: Black Ops 4]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/call-of-duty-black-ops-4-has-a-battle-royale-mode/1100-6459017/|title=Call Of Duty: Black Ops 4 Has A Battle Royale Mode|last=Knezevic|first=Kevin|date=May 17, 2018|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|access-date=May 17, 2018}}</ref> as does EA's ''[[Battlefield V]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/battlefield-5-battle-royale-mode-dice-discusses-ho/1100-6459565/ | title = Battlefield 5 Battle Royale Mode: DICE Discusses How It Happened | first = Eddie | last = Makuch | date = June 11, 2018 | accessdate = June 11, 2018 | work = [[GameSpot]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180610091712/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/battlefield-5-battle-royale-mode-dice-discusses-ho/1100-6459565/ | archivedate = June 10, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Other established games added battle royale-inspired gamemodes in updates, such as ''[[Grand Theft Auto Online]]'',<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/gta-online-gets-a-pubg-style-battle-royale-mode-in-the-smugglers-run-update/ | title = GTA Online gets a PUBG-style Battle Royale mode in the Smuggler's Run update | first = Andy | last = Chalk | date = August 29, 2017 | accessdate = September 12, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170913043922/http://www.pcgamer.com/gta-online-gets-a-pubg-style-battle-royale-mode-in-the-smugglers-run-update/ | archivedate = September 13, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''[[Paladins (video game)|Paladins]]'',<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/hi-rez-president-explains-why-battlegrounds-name-was-chosen-for-paladins-new-mode/ | title = Hi-Rez president explains why 'Battlegrounds' name was chosen for Paladins' new mode | first = Joe | last = Donnelly | date = January 5, 2018 | accessdate = January 5, 2018 | work = [[PC Gamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180105233645/http://www.pcgamer.com/hi-rez-president-explains-why-battlegrounds-name-was-chosen-for-paladins-new-mode/ | archivedate = January 5, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''[[Dota 2]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stewart|first1=Sam|title=Dota 2 Is Getting a Battle Royale Game Mode|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/05/08/dota-2-is-getting-a-battle-royale-game-mode|website=IGN|accessdate=May 9, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509023603/http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/05/08/dota-2-is-getting-a-battle-royale-game-mode|archivedate=May 9, 2018|date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Battlerite]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wood|first1=Austin|title=MOBA brawler Battlerite is getting a battle royale mode|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/moba-brawler-battlerite-is-getting-a-battle-royale-mode/|website=PC Gamer|accessdate=May 9, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510115244/https://www.pcgamer.com/moba-brawler-battlerite-is-getting-a-battle-royale-mode/|archivedate=May 10, 2018|date=May 3, 2018}}</ref> and ''[[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-12-06-counter-strike-global-offensive-goes-free-to-play | title=  Counter-Strike: Global Offensive goes free-to-play | first = Rebekah | last = Valentine | date = December 6, 2018 | accessdate = December 6, 2018 | work = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] }}</ref> In February 2019, EA released the free-to-play ''[[Apex Legends]]'', which exceeded 50 million player accounts within a month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/03/apex_legends_reaches_50_million_players_in_its_first_month|title=Apex Legends Reaches 50 Million Players In Its First Month|last=Tailby|first=Stephen|work=Push Square|date=March 4, 2019|accessdate=March 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304142048/http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/03/apex_legends_reaches_50_million_players_in_its_first_month|archive-date=March 4, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe battle royale approach has also been used in games from genres not normally associated with shooter games. ''[[Tetris 99]]'' is a 2019 game released by [[Nintendo]] for the [[Nintendo Switch]] that has 99 players simultaneously competing in a game of ''Tetris''. Players can direct \"attacks\" on other players for each line they complete, attempting to remain the last player standing.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/13/18224020/tetris-99-battle-royale-nintendo-switch-fortnite | title = Tetris is now a battle royale game with Tetris 99 | first = Julia | last = Alexander | date = February 13, 2019 | accessdate = February 13, 2019 | work = [[The Verge]] }}</ref> [[Blizzard Entertainment]] added a battle royale-inspired \"Battlegrounds\" mode to its digital card game ''[[Hearthstone]]'', where eight players vie to win over the others through several rounds of [[Draft (sports)|drafting]] new cards and fighting in one-on-one events.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/353607/Why_the_Hearthstone_devs_wanted_to_make_an_auto_battler.php | title = Why the Hearthstone devs wanted to make an auto battler | first = Bryant | last= Francis | date = November 11, 2019 | accessdate = December 11, 2019  |work = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref> The racing game ''[[Forza Horizon 4]]'' from [[Playground Games]] added a battle royale mode called \"The Eliminator\" where players all start with the same car, but can gain upgrades by beating other players and discovering \"drops\" around the map.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-12-11-forza-horizon-4-is-getting-a-battle-royale-mode-called-the-eliminator | title = Forza Horizon 4 is getting a battle royale mode called The Eliminator | first = Matt | last = Wales | date = December 11, 2019 | accessdate= December 11, 2019 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref>\n\n{{asof|2019|12}} dozens of battle royale games have debuted but, similar to the [[MOBA]] genre, only two or three titles have maintained mainstream popularity at the same time. Other games and battle royale modes had briefly become popular before their concurrent player count dropped and players returned to ''Fortnite'' or ''Battlegrounds''; ''Apex Legends'' was the year's only new successful battle royale game.<ref name=\"livingston20191211\">{{Cite magazine |last=Livingston |first=Christopher |date=2019-12-11 |title=How battle royale changed the last decade of games (and the next one) |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/how-battle-royale-changed-the-last-decade-of-games-and-the-next-one/ |magazine=PC Gamer |language=en-US |access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref> In contrast to other multiplayer-only games, the large number of players typically involved in battle royale games generally require a large enough concurrent player base for matchmaking in a reasonable amount of time. ''[[The Culling (video game)|The Culling]]'', by Xaviant Studios, was released in early access in 2016, and was designed to be a [[Live streaming|streaming-friendly]] battle royale mode for 16 players.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/270158/Making_a_battle_royale_for_players_and_viewers_alike_in_The_Culling.php | title = Making a battle royale for players and viewers alike in The Culling | first = Joel | last = Couture | date = April 13, 2016 | accessdate = September 22, 2017 | work = [[Gamasutra]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170923095513/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/270158/Making_a_battle_royale_for_players_and_viewers_alike_in_The_Culling.php | archivedate = September 23, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> However, following the release of ''Battlegrounds'', ''The Culling'' lost much of its player base, and a few months after releasing the full version of the game, Xaviant announced they were ending further development on it to move onto other projects.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/development-of-the-culling-has-come-to-a-halt/ | title = Development of The Culling has come to a halt | first = Andy | last = Chalk | date = December 18, 2017 | accessdate = December 18, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171219041946/http://www.pcgamer.com/development-of-the-culling-has-come-to-a-halt/ | archivedate = December 19, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''[[Radical Heights]]'' by [[Boss Key Productions]] was launched in April 2018 but within two weeks had lost 80% of its player base.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.destructoid.com/radical-heights-seems-to-be-hemorrhaging-players-500768.phtml | title = Radical Heights seems to be hemorrhaging players | first = Peter | last= Glagowski | date = April 28, 2018 | accessdate = October 12, 2018 | work = [[Destructoid]] }}</ref> ''SOS'', a battle royale game released by Outpost Games in December 2017, had its player counts drop into the double-digits by May 2018, leading Outpost to announce the game's closure by November 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamer.com/sos-the-battle-royale-you-can-win-with-your-voice-is-closing-in-november/  |title = SOS, the battle royale you can win with your voice, is closing in November | first = Andy | last = Chalk | date = October 12, 2018 | access-date = October 12, 2018 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref> While several major battle royale announcements occurred at [[E3]] in 2018, only ''[[Fallout 76]]''{{'}}s battle royale mode appeared at the trade show in 2019.{{r|livingston20191211}}\n\nThe [[Chinese government]], through its Audio and Video and Numeral Publishing Association, stated in October 2017 that it will discourage its citizens from playing battle royale games as they deem them too violent, which \"deviates from the values of socialism and is deemed harmful to young consumers\", as translated by ''[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-30/world-s-hottest-pc-game-could-be-banned-in-china-due-to-violence | title = World's Hottest PC Game Could Get Locked Out of China | first = Lulu Yilun | last = Chen | date = October 29, 2017 | accessdate = October 31, 2017 | work = [[Bloomberg Businessweek]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171030091807/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-30/world-s-hottest-pc-game-could-be-banned-in-china-due-to-violence | archivedate = October 30, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Gaming publications in the west speculated that this would make it difficult or impossible to publish battle royale within the country.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamesn.com/playerunknown-battlegrounds/pubg-china | title = The Chinese government is discouraging the development of battle royale games | first = Ali | last = Jones | date = October 30, 2017 | accessdate = October 30, 2017 | work = [[PCGamesN]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171030185708/https://www.pcgamesn.com/playerunknown-battlegrounds/pubg-china | archivedate = October 30, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> In November 2017, PUBG Corporation announced its partnership with [[Tencent]]  to publish the game in China, making some changes in the game to \"make sure they accord with socialist core values, Chinese traditional culture and moral rules\" to satisfy Chinese regulations and censors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-11-22-tencent-to-publish-playerunknowns-battlegrounds-in-china |title=Tencent to publish PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds in China |first=Matthew |last=Handrahan |date=November 22, 2017 |accessdate=November 22, 2017 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044018/http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-11-22-tencent-to-publish-playerunknowns-battlegrounds-in-china |archivedate=December 1, 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{citation | url = https://www.vg247.com/2017/11/22/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-has-been-approved-in-china-with-a-few-changes/ | title = PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds has been approved in China, with a few changes | first = Marshall | last = Lemon | date = November 22, 2017 | accessdate = November 22, 2017 | work = [[VG247]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171122161352/https://www.vg247.com/2017/11/22/playerunknowns-battlegrounds-has-been-approved-in-china-with-a-few-changes/ | archivedate = November 22, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-tencent-videogames/tencent-to-bring-worlds-hottest-video-game-to-china-promises-socialist-values-idUSKBN1DM192?feedType=RSS&feedName=technologyNews | title = Tencent to bring world's hottest video game to China, promises socialist values | date = November 22, 2017 | accessdate = December 15, 2017 | newspaper = [[Reuters]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171216034938/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-tencent-videogames/tencent-to-bring-worlds-hottest-video-game-to-china-promises-socialist-values-idUSKBN1DM192?feedType=RSS&feedName=technologyNews | archivedate = December 16, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> However, during mid-2018, the Chinese government revamped how it reviewed and classified games that are to be published in China, and by December 2018, after the formation of the new Online Ethics Review Committee, several battle royale titles, including ''Fortnite'' and ''PUBG'', were listed as prohibited or must be withdrawn from play.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamesn.com/fortnite/fortnite-china-ban | title=  Fortnite, PUBG, and Paladins have reportedly been banned by the Chinese government | first = Ali | last = Jones | date = December 11, 2018 | accessdate = December 11, 2018 | work = [[PCGamesN]] }}</ref> Despite the concern that PUBG Corporation and Tencent were taking with Chinese release, many [[video game clone|clones]] of ''Battlegrounds'' have been released in China already, and created a new genre there called \"chicken-eating game\", named based on the congratulatory line  to the last player standing in ''Battlegrounds'', \"Winner winner chicken dinner!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/310581/Inside_the_PUBGfueled_rise_of_chicken_eating_games_in_China.php|title=Inside the PUBG-fueled rise of 'chicken eating games' in China|first=Alex|last=Wawro|date=November 28, 2017|access-date=December 18, 2017|work=[[Gamasutra]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171227122651/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/310581/Inside_the_PUBGfueled_rise_of_chicken_eating_games_in_China.php|archive-date=December 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nThe rapid growth and success of the battle royale genre has been attributed to several factors, including the way all players start in the same vulnerable state and eliminating any intrinsic advantage for players, and being well-suited for being a spectator eSport.<ref name=\"wired maslow\"/> Other factors including specific games' business models, such as ''Fortnite Battle Royale'' being free and available across computers, consoles, and mobile devices.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/05/21/how-fortnite-captured-teens-hearts-and-minds | title = How Fortnite Captured Teens' Hearts and Minds | first = Nick | last = Paumgarten | date = May 15, 2018 | accessdate = May 15, 2018 | work = [[The New Yorker]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180515040304/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/05/21/how-fortnite-captured-teens-hearts-and-minds | archivedate = May 15, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> A [[University of Utah]] professor also considers that battle royale games realize elements of [[Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs]], a scheme to describe human motivation, more-so than video games have in the past. While the lowest tiers of Maslow's hierarchy, physiological and safety, are met by the survival elements of battle royales, the love/belonging and esteem tiers are a result of the battle royale being necessarily a social and competitive game, and the final tier of self-actualization comes from becoming skilled in the game to win frequently.<ref name=\"wired maslow\">{{cite web | url = https://www.wired.com/story/fortnite-battlefield-rise-of-battle-royale/ | title = WHY BATTLE ROYALE GAMES LIKE FORTNITE ARE EVERYWHERE (IT'S NOT JUST MONEY) | first = Carter | last = Melrose | date = June 14, 2018 | accessdate = June 14, 2018 | work = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180615011914/https://www.wired.com/story/fortnite-battlefield-rise-of-battle-royale/ | archivedate = June 15, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n''[[Business Insider]]'' projected that battle royale games would bring in over {{USD|2 billion|long=no}} during 2018, and would grow to {{USD|20 billion|long=no}} in 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/07/20/analysts-predict-battle-royale-games-could-make-20-billion-next-year | title = Analysts Predict Battle Royale Games Could Make $20 Billion Next Year | first = Jessie | last = Wade | date = July 20, 2018 | accessdate = July 20, 2018 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref> SuperData Research reported that, [[2018 in video gaming|in 2018]], the three top-grossing battle royale games (''Fortnite'', ''PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds'' and ''Call of Duty: Black Ops 4'') generated nearly {{US$|4 billion|long=no}} in combined digital revenue.<ref>{{cite web |title=Market Brief {{ndash}} 2018 Digital Games & Interactive Entertainment Industry Year In Review |url=https://www.superdataresearch.com/market-data/market-brief-year-in-review/ |website=SuperData Research |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref> Sensor Tower reported that 2018's top three [[List of most-played mobile games by player count|most-downloaded mobile]] battle royale games (''[[PUBG Mobile]]'', ''[[Garena Free Fire]]'' and ''Fortnite'') received over 500{{nbsp}}million downloads combined that year.<ref name=\"sensortower\">{{cite web |title=Q4 and Full Year 2018: Store Intelligence Data Digest |url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/sensortower-itunes/Quarterly+Reports/Sensor-Tower-Q4-2018-Data-Digest.pdf |website=Sensor Tower  |date=January 16, 2019 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref> The [[List of most-played video games|most-played]] battle royale games include ''PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds'' with over 555{{nbsp}}million players,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Partleton |first1=Kayleigh |title=PUBG Mobile shoots through $1.5 billion in lifetime revenue |url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/asia/news/72145/pubg-mobile-1500000000-lifetime-revenue/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[Pocket Gamer]] |date=December 12, 2019}}</ref> [[NetEase]]'s mobile game ''Knives Out'' with over 250{{nbsp}}million players,<ref name=\"gamasutra\"/> ''Fortnite Battle Royale'' with nearly 250{{nbsp}}million players,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.engadget.com/2019/03/20/fortnite-250-million-epic-games-sweeney-interview-gdc/ | title = Epic Games has 250 million 'Fortnite' players and a lot of plans | first = Jessica | last = Conditt | date = March 20, 2019 | accessdate = March 20, 2019 | work = [[Engadget]] }}</ref> ''[[Rules of Survival]]'' with 230{{nbsp}}million players,<ref name=\"NetEase\"/> and ''Garena Free Fire'' with over 180{{nbsp}}million players.<ref name=\"sensortower\"/>\n\n[[Turtle Beach Corporation]], a manufacturer of headphones and microphones for gaming, reported an increase of over 200% in net revenues for the second quarter of 2018 over the same quarter in 2017, which they attributed to the popularity of the battle royale genre.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/323907/The_battle_royale_boom_helped_Turtle_Beach_achieve_a_record_quarter.php | title = The battle royale boom helped Turtle Beach achieve a record quarter | first=  Alissa | last =McAloon | date = August 7, 2018 | accessdate = August 7, 2018 | work = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Battle royal]]\n* [[Deathmatch]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Video game genre}}\n\n[[Category:Video game genres]]\n[[Category:Battle royale games| ]]\n[[Category:21st-century neologisms]]\n[[Category:2010s fads and trends]]\n[[Category:2020s fads and trends]]\n", "name_user": "Ayenaee", "label": "safe", "comment": "Importing Wikidatashort description: \"Video game genre with the last-man-standing gameplay\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_royale_game"}
